{"title_page": "Bartholdi Fountain", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Flickr - USCapitol - Bartholdi Fountain (1).jpg\n| caption            = The restored Bartholdi Fountain illuminated, summer of 2011, from the [[Architect of the Capitol]]\n| painting_alignment =  \n| image_upright      = 1\n| title              = Bartholdi Fountain\n| italic title       = no\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = The Bartholdi Fountain in Washington D.C. (1876)\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi\n| year               = 1876\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric      = \n| width_metric       = \n| length_metric      = \n| height_imperial    = 30\n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| diameter__metric   = \n| diameter_imperial  = \n| imperial_unit      = ft\n| metric_unit        = cm\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38.887127|-77.012669|region:US_type:landmark|}}\n| owner              = [[United States Botanic Garden]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Bartholdi Fountain''' is a monumental public [[fountain]], designed by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]], who later created the [[Statue of Liberty]]. The fountain was originally made for the [[1876 Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], and is now located at the corner of [[Independence Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Independence Avenue]] and First Street, [[Southwest, Washington, D.C.|SW]], in the [[United States Botanic Garden]], on the grounds of the [[United States Capitol]], in [[Washington D.C.]].<ref name=siris>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1J02H177103Y5.5404&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Bartholdi+Fountain+&aspect=Keyword&x=12&y=14 \"The Bartholdi Fountain, (sculpture)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916235543/https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1J02H177103Y5.5404&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=1&source=%257E%2521siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Bartholdi+Fountain+&aspect=Keyword&x=12&y=14|date=2012-09-16}}.  ''Art Inventories, Smithsonian American Art Museum.''  Smithsonian Institution Research Information System (SIRIS)</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Bartholdi fountain, by Centennial Photographic Co..png|thumb|left|Stereoscopic albumen print of the Bartholdi fountain, by Centennial Photographic Co., 1876, from the [[New York Public Library]] ]]\n\nThe '''''Fountain of Light and Water''''',<ref name=usbg />  commonly called  the Bartholdi fountain, was created for the 1876 Philadelphia Exposition which celebrated the 100th birthday of the United States.  It was designed by French sculptor [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]], and it was cast by the Durenne foundry in France, which had won awards for its cast-iron fountains at earlier international expositions in 1862, 1867 and 1873.<ref>Frances R. Kowsky, ''The Bartholdi Fountain: A Model for All Our Cities'', Gazette des Beaux Arts, sec. 6, volume 94, December 1979. pp. 231\u2013237.</ref> Bartholdi offered the fountain to the Exposition for free; he intended to sell it afterwards, and to sell others of the same design to other cities. The fountains stood at the center of the esplanade, near the main entrance to the exposition.\n\nWhen the exposition ended in 1877, Bartholdi did not find any buyers for his fountain. One year later it was purchased by the United States Congress, which offered him only six thousand dollars, half the sum he had originally asked. In 1878, it was placed at the base of Capitol Hill in Washington, D.C.   In 1926 it was removed and stored to facilitate completion of the [[George Gordon Meade Memorial]], and for landscaping improvements around the Grant Memorial.<ref name=siris />  In 1932, the sculpture was placed at its current location in the [[United States Botanic Garden]], on the grounds of the [[United States Capitol]],<ref name=usbg>{{cite web|title=Bartholdi Park|url=http://www.usbg.gov/bartholdi-park|work=United States Botanic Garden|publisher=Architect of the Capitol|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Bartholdi Fountain in Washington, D.C. 2012.JPG|thumb|The restored Bartholdi Fountain in Washington, D.C., 2012]]\n\nIn 2008 the Architect of the Capitol began a complete restoration of the fountain and its basin, the first complete deconstruction and restoration since 1927. The restoration repaired deterioration to the metals inside and out, and also provided modern pumps and motors, a new water treatment and filtration system, and a zinc coating to preserve the original cast-iron of the fountain.   The fountain was returned to [[Bartholdi Park]] in spring 2011.<ref name=aoc>{{cite web|title=Bartholdi Fountain and Park|url=http://www.aoc.gov/capitol-buildings/bartholdi-fountain-and-park|work=Explore Capitol Hill|publisher=Architect of the Capitol|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe fountain is composed of a series of basins, supported by sculptures of classical figures. The cast iron is coated with bronze, stands thirty feet high, and weighs thirty thousand pounds.  It stands in the center of a large circular marble pool. \n\nThree figures of women, standing on a triangle pedestal with an ornamental design of seas shells and three reptiles spouting water, support the lower cast iron vasque, which is adorned with a circle of twelve lamps. In the center, three kneeling tritons support another, smaller and higher vasque. Water spouts from a crown at the top, cascades down into the smaller vasque, and then down into the larger vasque before spilling into the main basin. The cascade of water was illuminated by the gas lamps (later replaced with electric globes), making it one of the first monuments in Washington, D.C. to be lit at night, and therefore a popular evening destination in the 1880s.<ref name=siris />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n== Citations ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Marilyn Symmes, editor, ''Fountains: Splash and Spectacle&mdash;Water and Design from the Renaissance to the Present'', Thames and Hudson, in association with Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, Smithsonian Institution, 1998. \n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/washdc/bartholdi/bartholdi.html The Bartholdi Fountain], digital imaging project by Mary Ann Sullivan, Bluffton University. 2002.\n\n{{Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n[[Category:1876 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Fountains in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Relocated buildings and structures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]]\n[[Category:Seashells in art]]\n[[Category:United States Capitol grounds]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Southwest Federal Center]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Flickr - USCapitol - Bartholdi Fountain (1).jpg\n| caption = The restored Bartholdi Fountain illuminated, summer of 2011, from the [[Architect of the Capitol]]\n| painting_alignment =  \n| image_size         = 250px\n| title              = Bartholdi Fountain\n| alt                = \n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      =The Bartholdi Fountain in Washington D.C. (1876)\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      = \n| artist             = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi\n| year               = 1876\n| type               = Bronze\n| height_metric          = \n| width_metric           = \n| length_metric          = \n| height_imperial        = 30\n| width_imperial         = \n| length_imperial        = \n| diameter__metric       = \n| diameter_imperial      = \n| imperial_unit = ft\n| metric_unit = cm\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = \n| coordinates        = {{Coord|38.887127|-77.012669|region:US_type:landmark|}}\n| owner              = [[United States Botanic Garden]] }}\n\nThe '''Bartholdi Fountain''' is a monumental public [[fountain]], designed by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]], who later created the [[Statue of Liberty]]. The fountain was originally made for the [[1876 Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], and is now located at the corner of [[Independence Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Independence Avenue]] and First Street, [[Southwest, Washington, D.C.|SW]], in the [[United States Botanic Garden]], on the grounds of the [[United States Capitol]], in [[Washington D.C.]].<ref name=siris>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1J02H177103Y5.5404&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=1&source=~!siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Bartholdi+Fountain+&aspect=Keyword&x=12&y=14 \"The Bartholdi Fountain, (sculpture)\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916235543/https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1J02H177103Y5.5404&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=1&source=%257E%2521siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Bartholdi+Fountain+&aspect=Keyword&x=12&y=14|date=2012-09-16}}.  ''Art Inventories, Smithsonian American Art Museum.''  Smithsonian Institution Research Information System (SIRIS)</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Bartholdi fountain, by Centennial Photographic Co..png|thumb|left|Stereoscopic albumen print of the Bartholdi fountain, by Centennial Photographic Co., 1876, from the [[New York Public Library]] ]]\n\nThe '''''Fountain of Light and Water''''',<ref name=usbg />  commonly called  the Bartholdi fountain, was created for the 1876 Philadelphia Exposition which celebrated the 100th birthday of the United States.  It was designed by French sculptor [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi]], and it was cast by the Durenne foundry in France, which had won awards for its cast-iron fountains at earlier international expositions in 1862, 1867 and 1873.<ref>Frances R. Kowsky, ''The Bartholdi Fountain: A Model for All Our Cities'', Gazette des Beaux Arts, sec. 6, volume 94, December 1979. pp. 231-237.</ref> Bartholdi offered the fountain to the Exposition for free; he intended to sell it afterwards, and to sell others of the same design to other cities. The fountains stood at the center of the esplanade, near the main entrance to the exposition.\n\nWhen the exposition ended in 1877, Bartholdi did not find any buyers for his fountain. One year later it was purchased by the United States Congress, which offered him only six thousand dollars, half the sum he had originally asked. In 1878, it was placed at the base of Capitol Hill in Washington, D.C.   In 1926 it was removed and stored to facilitate completion of the [[George Gordon Meade Memorial]], and for landscaping improvements around the Grant Memorial.<ref name=siris />  In 1932, the sculpture was placed at its current location in the [[United States Botanic Garden]], on the grounds of the [[United States Capitol]],<ref name=usbg>{{cite web|title=Bartholdi Park|url=http://www.usbg.gov/bartholdi-park|work=United States Botanic Garden|publisher=Architect of the Capitol|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Bartholdi Fountain in Washington, D.C. 2012.JPG|thumb|The restored Bartholdi Fountain in Washington, D.C., 2012]]\n\nIn 2008 the Architect of the Capitol began a complete restoration of the fountain and its basin, the first complete deconstruction and restoration since 1927. The restoration repaired deterioration to the metals inside and out, and also provided modern pumps and motors, a new water treatment and filtration system, and a zinc coating to preserve the original cast-iron of the fountain.   The fountain was returned to [[Bartholdi Park]] in spring 2011.<ref name=aoc>{{cite web|title=Bartholdi Fountain and Park|url=http://www.aoc.gov/capitol-buildings/bartholdi-fountain-and-park|work=Explore Capitol Hill|publisher=Architect of the Capitol|accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe fountain is composed of a series of basins, supported by sculptures of classical figures. The cast iron is coated with bronze, stands thirty feet high, and weighs thirty thousand pounds.  It stands in the center of a large circular marble pool. \n\nThree figures of women, standing on a triangle pedestal with an ornamental design of seas shells and three reptiles spouting water, support the lower cast iron vasque, which is adorned with a circle of twelve lamps. In the center, three kneeling tritons support another, smaller and higher vasque. Water spouts from a crown at the top, cascades down into the smaller vasque, and then down into the larger vasque before spilling into the main basin. The cascade of water was illuminated by the gas lamps (later replaced with electric globes), making it one of the first monuments in Washington, D.C. to be lit at night, and therefore a popular evening destination in the 1880s.<ref name=siris />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 6]]\n\n== Citations ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Marilyn Symmes, editor, ''Fountains- Splash and Spectacle- Water and Design from the Renaissance to the Present'', Thames and Hudson, in association with Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, Smithsonian Institution, 1998. \n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/washdc/bartholdi/bartholdi.html The Bartholdi Fountain], digital imaging project by Mary Ann Sullivan, Bluffton University. 2002.\n\n{{Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auguste Bartholdi}}\n\n[[Category:1876 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Fountains in Washington, D.C.]]\n[