{"title_page": "2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary", "text_new": "{{current election|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary\n| country = Wisconsin\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2016 Wisconsin Democratic primary\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = 2024 Wisconsin Democratic primary\n| next_year = 2024\n| election_date = April 7, 2020\n| outgoing_members = [[2020 Illinois Democratic primary|IL]]\n| elected_members = [[2020 Alaska Democratic primary|AK]]\n| votes_for_election = 97 [[2020 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] delegates (84 pledged, 13 unpledged)<br>The number of pledged delegates won is determined by the popular vote\n| candidates = \n| image1 = [[File:Joe Biden February 2020 crop.jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate1 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| color1 = 224192\n| home_state1 = [[Delaware]]\n| delegate_count1 = \n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n| image2 = [[File:Bernie Sanders March 2020 (cropped).jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate2 = [[Bernie Sanders]] <!--Please do not remove Sanders, as he dropped out after voting in the Wisconsin primary ended.-->\n| color2 = 228b22\n| home_state2 = [[Vermont]]\n| delegate_count2 = \n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n| party_name = no\n| map_image = \n| map_size = \n| map_caption = -->\n}}\n{{Elections in Wisconsin}}\n\nThe '''2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary''' took place on Tuesday, April 7, 2020, in the midst of a global pandemic, along with the Wisconsin Supreme Court Justice election. It is one of the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic Party presidential primaries]] for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]]. The Wisconsin primary is an [[open primary]], with the state awarding 97 delegates, of which 84 are pledged delegates allocated on the basis of the results of the primary. Although in-person voting took place on April 7, full results are not expected until April 13, in accordance with a district court ruling.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Larsen |first1=Emily |title=An awkward coronavirus Democratic primary in Wisconsin |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/an-awkward-coronavirus-democratic-primary-in-wisconsin |accessdate=8 April 2020 |publisher=The Washington Examiner |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of the primary on April 7, Joe Biden and Bernie Sanders were in the race. However, the next morning, before any of Wisconsin's results were released, Sanders dropped out of the race, leaving Biden as the party's presumed presidential nominee.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Sean|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bernie-sanders-to-end-his-presidential-campaign/2020/03/18/cf7a1824-4d18-11ea-9b5c-eac5b16dafaa_story.html|title=Bernie Sanders to end his presidential campaign|date=8 April 2020|work=Washington Post|access-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Janes|first2=Chelsea}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\nWisconsin was the sole state that voted on April 7, 2020, in the Democratic primaries.<ref name=\"FHQ-primarydates\">{{cite web|last1=Putnam|first1=Josh|title=The 2020 Presidential Primary Calendar|url=https://frontloading.blogspot.com/p/2020-presidential-primary-calendar.html|publisher=Frontloading HQ|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVoting took place throughout the state from 7:00&nbsp;a.m. until 8:00&nbsp;p.m. In the open primary, candidates must meet a threshold of 15% at the congressional district or statewide level in order to be considered viable. The 84 pledged delegates to the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]] will be allocated proportionally on the basis of the results of the primary. Of the 77 pledged delegates, between 5 and 11 are allocated to each of the [[Wisconsin's congressional districts|state's 8 congressional districts]] and another 10 are allocated to party leaders and elected officials (PLEO delegates), in addition to 29 at-large pledged delegates. These delegate totals do not account for pledged delegate bonuses or penalties from timing or clustering.<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite web|title=Wisconsin Democratic Delegation 2020|url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/P20/WI-D|publisher=The Green Papers|date=May 3, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday, April 26, 2020, county caucuses will select delegates for congressional district caucuses which will take place on Sunday, May 17, 2020, which in turn designate national convention district-level delegates. The administrative committee meeting before the state convention will subsequently be on Friday, June 12, 2020, to vote on the 29 pledged at-large and 10 PLEO delegates to send to the Democratic National Convention. The 77 pledged delegates Wisconsin sends to the national convention will be joined by 13 unpledged PLEO delegates (eight members of the [[Democratic National Committee]]; four members of Congress, including one Senator and 3 U.S. Representatives; and the governor).<ref name=\"GP\"/>\n\n=== 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic ===\n{{seealso|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics#Wisconsin}}\nSince the outbreak of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], several states delayed their scheduled primaries and extending the vote-by-mail period. Concerns were raised by health officials, poll workers, and voters that in-person voting at the height of the pandemic would be unsafe for vulnerable individuals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-election-wisconsin-idUSKBN21M0VX|title=Wisconsin set to hold in-person voting in presidential primary|date=2020-04-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en}}</ref> Governor [[Tony Evers]] (D) signed an executive order for all-mail-in election, but the order was rejected by the Republican-controlled [[Wisconsin Legislature]].<ref name=primaries>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/coronavirus-update-states-that-have-postponed-2020-primaries.html Coronavirus is disrupting the 2020 election. Here\u2019s a list of all the primaries that have been postponed] by Yelena Dzhanova, CNBC, 2 Apr 2020</ref>\n\nOn April 2, although U.S. District Judge [[William M. Conley]] refused to postpone the election, he extended the deadline for absentee voting to April 13 (ordering clerks not to release any election data before that date).<ref>{{cite web|website=AP |title=Wisconsin barrels ahead with election despite virus fears|author=Todd Richmond|date=April 3, 2020 |url=https://apnews.com/8a89da046f4d9ea1211fbf8030f033d7}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/491194-wisconsin-republicans-say-they-will-ask-supreme-court-to-block-extended|title=Wisconsin Republicans say they will ask Supreme Court to block extended absentee voting|last=Johnson|first=Martin|date=2020-04-04|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> However, on April 6, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] overturned Conley's decision, meaning that all absentee ballots must still be postmarked by \"election day, Tuesday, April 7\" even though it will still be acceptable for the ballots to be received by the clerks as late as April 13.<ref>{{cite web |title=Supreme Court blocks extended absentee voting in Wisconsin primary |url=https://www.channel3000.com/supreme-court-blocks-extended-absentee-voting-in-wisconsin-primary/ |website=Channel3000.com |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electionlawblog.org/wp-content/uploads/19A1016.pdf|title=REPUBLICAN NATIONAL COMMITTEE, ET AL. v. DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL COMMITTEE, ET AL. No. 19A1016|last=Supreme Court of the United States|first=|date=April 6, 2020|website=electionlawblog.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The [[Supreme Court of the United States]], \"did not alter the provision in Conley's amended order which prohibits the reporting of results until April 13\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elections.wi.gov/node/6824|title=URGENT -- Wisconsin Supreme Court Orders Election Day to Continue and U.S. Supreme Court Alters Ballot Receipt Deadline; Tallying and Reporting Results Still Prohibited Until April 13 - COVID-19 {{!}} Wisconsin Elections Commission|website=elections.wi.gov|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Evers then called a special session of the legislature to postpone in-person voting, but the session ended within minutes without action, forcing the primary to go on as planned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/2020/04/04/wisconsin-legislature-adjourns-special-session-monday-voting-track-tuesday-election/2948444001/|title=In matter of seconds, Republicans stall Gov. Tony Evers' move to postpone Tuesday election|first1=Bill|last1=Glauber|first2=Patrick|last2=Marley|website=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel}}</ref>\n\nDespite admitting that he would violate the law by doing so,<ref>[http://www.belling.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/evers1.pdf Governor Evers Tweet April 1 2020]</ref> on April 6, Evers issued an [[Executive order#State executive orders|executive order]] which, if enforced, would have postponed the April 7 elections until the tentative date of June 9.<ref name=cnnapril6>{{cite web |last1=CNN |first1=Eric Bradner and Kate Sullivan |title=Wisconsin governor orders delay of primary election until June |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/06/politics/wisconsin-primary-election/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/election-2020/ct-wisconsin-primary-election-supreme-court-20200406-bzrppmmapnhg3aatqo2d4c5yza-story.html|title=Wisconsin governor issues executive order to delay Tuesday\u2019s election until June|first=Bill|last=Ruthhart|website=chicagotribune.com}}</ref> Republican leaders immediately announced that they would challenge the order in the [[Wisconsin Supreme Court]].<ref name=cnnapril6/> The Wisconsin Supreme Court ruled that Evers did not have the authority to postpone the elections, thus meaning that Evers' executive order was nullified, and that the elections would be held as scheduled on April 7.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wisconsin Supreme Court rules Evers cannot postpone election |url=https://www.wisn.com/article/wisconsin-election-moves-ahead-awaits-supreme-court/32018135 |website=WISN |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |language=en |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis was appealed to a federal court who sided with the Governor, and that was appealed to the US Supreme Court, which on a 5\u20134 vote, upheld the State court's ruling.<ref>https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/scotus-wisconsin-election/</ref> \n\nVoting was somewhat chaotic, with people waiting in the rain for hours in some cases in masks and social distancing.<ref>https://www.axios.com/wisconsin-results-coronavirus-supreme-court-0715ee50-a85b-41e8-a4ef-053290bc2692.html</ref> However, by the time the election concluded, Milwaukee Election Commissioner Neil Albrecht stated that despite some of the problems, the in-person voting ran smoothly.<ref>[https://www.wuwm.com/post/milwaukee-election-chief-despite-some-issues-person-voting-went-smoothly#stream/0 Milwaukee Election Chief: Despite Some Issues, In-Person Voting Went Smoothly]</ref>\n\n==Polling==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;text-align:center;\"\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" |Polling aggregation\n|- valign=bottom style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n!Source of poll aggregation\n!Date<br>updated\n!Dates<br>polled\n![[Joe Biden|Joe<br>Biden]]\n![[Bernie Sanders|Bernie<br>Sanders]]\n!Other/<br>Undecided{{Efn|name=undecided|Calculated by taking the difference of 100% and all other candidates combined|group=}}\n|-\n|[https://www.270towin.com/2020-democratic-nomination/wisconsin-primary 270 to Win]\n|April 5, 2020\n|March 6\u201329, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''55.3%'''<!--Joe Biden-->\n|37.0%<!--Bernie Sanders-->\n|7.7%\n|-\n