.kff.org/attachment/TOPLINE-Blue-Wall-Voices-Project Kaiser Family Foundation]\n| Sep 23 \u2013 Oct 15, 2019\n| 274 (LV)\n| \u2013\n|17%\n| \u2013\n|2%\n|6%\n|3%\n|3%\n|10%\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''22%'''\n|2%\n|1%{{efn|O'Rourke with 1%; Steyer with 0%; Castro with no voters; other with 0%}}\n|{{party shading/Undecided}}|'''35%'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.foxnews.com/politics/fox-news-poll-results-september-29-october-2-2019-wisconsin Fox News]\n| Sep 29 \u2013 Oct 2, 2019\n| 663 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.5%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''28%'''\n| \u2013\n| 2%\n| 7%\n| 5%\n| 2%\n| 17%\n| 22%\n| 2%\n| 5%{{efn|Bullock, Gabbard and O'Rourke with 1%; Bennet, Delaney, Ryan, Sestak, Steyer, Williamson and Other with <1%; Castro and Messam with 0%; None of the above with 1%|name=|group=}}\n| 9%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://law.marquette.edu/poll/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/MLSP53Toplines.pdf Marquette University Law School]\n| Aug 25\u201329, 2019\n| 444 (RV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;5.3%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''28%'''\n| \u2013\n| 1%\n| 6%\n| 3%\n| 1%\n| 20%\n| 17%\n| 2%\n| 5%{{efn|\"Someone else\", Bullock, Gillibrand, O'Rourke, Steyer with 1%; Bennet, Gabbard, Delaney, Castro, Ryan and Williamson with 0%}}\n| 13%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.changeresearch.com/crooked-change-wisconsin-aug-2019 Change Research]\n| Aug 9\u201311, 2019\n| 935 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;3.2%\n| 20%\n| \u2013\n| 1%\n| 9%\n| 5%\n| 2%\n| 24%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''29%'''\n| 2%\n| 5%{{efn|Gabbard with 2%; Inslee, O'Rourke, Steyer, and Williamson with 1%; Bennet, Bullock, Castro, Delaney, Gillibrand, Hickenlooper, Messam, and Sestak with 0%}}\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://www.changeresearch.com/wisconsin-poll-sept-29-oct-2 Change Research]\n| Jun 29 \u2013 Jul 4, 2019\n| 1261 (LV)\n| \u2013 \n| 18%\n| \u2013\n| 3%\n| 15%\n| 17%\n| 1%\n|'''19%'''\n|'''19%'''\n| 1%\n| 6%{{efn|Gabbard and O'Rourke with 2%; Castro, Delaney, Gillibrand and Inslee with 1%; Bennet, Bullock, Gravel, Hickenlooper, Moulton, Ryan, Swalwell and Williamson with 0%; Messam and Sestak with no voters}}\n| \u2013\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/20190615_National.xlsx Zogby Analytics]\n| May 23\u201329, 2019\n| 238 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;6.4%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''28%'''\n| \u2013\n| 2%\n| 7%\n| 7%\n| 3%\n| 13%\n| 14%\n| 0%\n| 2%{{efn|Castro, Gabbard, Gillibrand, and O'Rourke with 1%; Delaney, Hickenlooper, Inslee, and Yang with 0%}}\n| \u2013\n|- style=\"background:lightyellow;\"\n| style=\"border-right-style:hidden;\"|\n| style=\"border-right-style:hidden;\"| Apr 25, 2019\n| colspan=\"13\" | Biden announces [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|his candidacy]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [https://zogbyanalytics.com/news/887-the-zogby-poll-biden-leads-in-the-badger-state-and-future-home-of-the-2020-democratic-convention-sanders-is-in-close-pursuit-in-2nd-place-but-mayor-pete-is-on-fire-in-3rd-place-kamala-harris-jumps-beto-o-rourke-and-elizabeth-warren-for-4th-place Zogby Analytics]\n| Apr 15\u201318, 2019\n| 485 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;4.5%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''24%'''\n| \u2013\n| 4%\n| 10%\n| 7%\n| 4%\n| 20%\n| 6%\n| 1%\n| 11%{{efn|O'Rourke with 5%; Hickenlooper with 2%; Castro, Gillibrand, and Yang with 1%; Delaney, Gabbard, and Inslee with 0%; others with 2%}}\n| 14%\n|- style=\"background:lightyellow;\"\n| style=\"border-right-style:hidden;\"|\n| style=\"border-right-style:hidden;\"| Apr 14, 2019\n| colspan=\"13\" | Buttigieg announces [[Pete Buttigieg 2020 presidential campaign|his candidacy]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [http://emersonpolling.com/2019/03/17/wisconsin-2020-bernie-sanders-leads-democratic-field-trump-competitive-in-general-election/ Emerson College]\n| Mar 15\u201317, 2019\n| 324 (LV)\n| \u00b1&nbsp;5.4%\n| 24%\n| \u2013\n| 2%\n| 1%\n| 5%\n| 4%\n| {{party shading/Democratic}}| '''39%'''\n| 14%\n| 1%\n| 10%{{efn|O'Rourke with 6%; Gillibrand with 1%; Castro, Gabbard, Hickenlooper, and Inslee with 0%; others with 3%}}\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+ style=\"background-color:#f2f2f2;margin-bottom:-1px;border:1px solid #aaa;padding:0.2em 0.4em;\" | 2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Candidate\n! Votes\n! %\n! Delegates\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Biden, Joe\" | [[Joe Biden]]\n|0\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Sanders, Bernie\" | [[Bernie Sanders]]\n|0\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Gabbard, Tulsi\" | [[Tulsi Gabbard]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Bloomberg, Michael\" | [[Michael Bloomberg]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Warren, Elizabeth\" | [[Elizabeth Warren]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n|0\n| \n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Buttigieg, Pete\" | [[Pete Buttigieg]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Klobuchar, Amy\" | [[Amy Klobuchar]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Bennet, Michael\" | [[Michael Bennet]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Delaney, John\" | [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Patrick, Deval\" | [[Deval Patrick]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Steyer, Tom\" | [[Tom Steyer]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n| 0\n| \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" data-sort-name=\"Yang, Andrew\" | [[Andrew Yang]] <small>(withdrawn)</small>\n| 0\n|0\n|\n|-\n! Total\n!0\n!0\n!0 (of 84)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n*[[2020 Wisconsin Republican primary]]\n*[[2020 Democratic National Convention]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thegreenpapers.com/P20/WI-D The Green Papers delegate allocation summary]\n*[https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primaries/democratic/wisconsin/ FiveThirtyEight Wisconsin primary poll tracker]\n*[https://www.scotusblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/19A1016.pdf ScotusBlog]\n{{2020 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States Democratic presidential primaries by state|Wisconsin Democratic]]\n[[Category:2020 Wisconsin elections|Democratic primary]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democratic primaries|2020]]\n", "name_user": "Kevinkevinn69", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Wisconsin_Democratic_primary"}
{"title_page": "R (March) v Secretary of State for Health", "text_new": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=51 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State.''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=19 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote= ''...that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h);''}}</ref> In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |pages=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down in Court 49 of the High Court by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010, the eve of [[World Federation of Hemophilia#World Hemophilia Day|\nWorld Haemophilia Day]] 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision&nbsp;\u2013 had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error to an existing fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact.''|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020 |quote=...the fact or evidence must have been \u2033established\u2033, in the sense that it was uncontentious and objectively verifiable;}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error;<ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''Thirdly, the appellant (or his advisers) must not been have been responsible for the mistake.''}}</ref> | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; in that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=53 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>}}\n\n===Reviewability of Evidence===\nThere was considerable scrutiny over the quality and type of evidence deemed permissible. The use of [[hansard]] was permitted by the court due to specific circumstances relating to the decision under review; in particular, the government\u2019s reasoning behind their decision.  Justice Holman made a clear statement they the court could not to go beyond the scope of reviewability and could not come to any conclusions about the proceedings of Parliament and whether they were in any way inadequate or inaccurate.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P29.4.10> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=338 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''The role of the court is limited to examining the decision under review.''}},</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nOn the morning the judgment was handed down, the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]] described how he felt the decision was historic for the haemophilia community and how he expected it would be welcomed by the community of some 5,000 people who were infected ''en masse'' with HIV and Hepatitis C through contaminated blood and blood products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/health/8624879.stm |title=Campaigner wins tainted blood case |date=16 April 2010 |website=BBC News |access-date= 2020-04-12}}</ref> Lord Morris went on to expand as follows:\n<blockquote>''\u20261,974 have died in direct consequence of the NHS treatment. Yet until today the legal road to redress was blocked, just as unbreakably as any prospect of securing justice by legislative means. Now with today\u2019s historic breakthrough in the High Court and the huge public backing for my Contaminated Blood Support for Infected and Bereaved Persons Bill, both roads are open. Our determination to ensure that \u2032right is done\u2032 is totally vindicated and a just outcome is now in sight.''<ref>{{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160506174652/http://taintedblood.info/news.php?mode=article&newsid=153 |date=May 6, 2016 |title= Haemophilia Society Welcomes Historic Victory in Court |author= Sue Threakall }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the weeks that followed the quashing of the decision, the government were required by the court to revisit the matter and remake the decision&nbsp;\u2013 ''de novo''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Farrell |first=Anne-Maree |date=2012 |title=The Politics of Blood: Ethics, Innovation and the Regulation of Risk |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HaRqhn75hH8C |location=Cambridge |publisher=Campridge University Press |page=142 |isbn=9780521193184}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "text_old": "{{coi|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|UK judicial review quashing a decision on the grounds of material error of fact}}\n{{italic title|all=yes}}\n\n{{Infobox court case\n| name = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health\n| image = \n| court = High Court\n| date decided = 16 April 2010\n| full name = The Queen (on the application of Andrew Michael March) v The Secretary of State for Health\n| citations = [2010] [https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html EWHC 765 (Admin)]\n| judges = [[James Holman (judge)|Mr Justice Holman]]\n| prior actions =  \n| subsequent actions = \n| opinions = \n| transcripts =\n| keywords = Material error of fact; Relevance of Hansard\n}}\n\n'''''R (March) v Secretary of State for Health''''' was a successful 2010 [[Judicial review in English law|judicial review]] which challenged the UK [[Department of Health and Social Care|Department of Health's]] decision not to implement Recommendation 6(h) of the Archer Independent Inquiry.<ref name=\"Bailii1\">{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57}}</ref> \nThe case was important in developing the doctrine of ''error of fact'' in [[public law]] which previously had not readily been the subject of judicial intervention.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=2008 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Fifth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=468 |isbn=9781841138244 |quote= ''Judicial review judges have traditionally been cautious about fact-based challenges''.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Demetriou |first1=Marie |last2= Houseman |first2= Stephen |date= 1997|title=Review for Error of Fact\u2014A Brief Guide |url= https://doi.org/10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 |journal=JR |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=27\u201332 |doi= 10.1080/10854681.1997.11426925 | publisher = Routledge |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=51 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2004/49.html}}</ref>\n\n==Facts==\n\n[[Andrew March|Andrew Michael March]], a [[haemophilia|haemophiliac]],<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |last1= Meikle |first1= James  |date= 2010-04-16 |title= Court ruling may help contaminated blood victims win higher payouts|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote= ''A classical music composer who was infected by HIV when he was nine, who later developed hepatitis, won a judicial review that challenged the basis of health ministers' decision last year not to increase the payments.''}}</ref> along with several thousand other patients was treated with contaminated blood products in the 1970\u2032s and 1980\u2032s.<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1= |date= 2010-04-16 |title=Composer wins compensation review over contaminated blood |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/7597423/Composer-wins-compensation-review-over-contaminated-blood.html|work=The Telegraph |location=London |access-date=2020-04-11 |quote=An award-winning composer who contracted HIV and Hepatitis C through NHS treatment with contaminated blood products has won a legal challenge over compensation payments.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood and blood products]] disaster also occurred in the [[Republic of Ireland]]<ref name=\"Bailii1\" /> and various compensation schemes and statutory provisions were put in place between 1991 and 2002 on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the state.<ref name=\"Hynes1\">{{cite letter| first = Lara| last = Hynes| recipient = Mark A. Ward| subject = RE: Blood & Tissue Policy Division, (DOHC)| language = English| date = {{date|2009-07-30|mdy}}| quote =''The scheme of compensation for persons with haemophilia was put in place on compassionate grounds, without legal liability on the part of the State.''}}</ref> However, the level of payments made to similarly infected and affected people in the Republic of Ireland was considerably greater than payments made to victims in the United Kingdom. In the UK, the Department of Health had consistently refused to increase the ''[[ex gratia]]'' support payments to be on a par with the more generous levels of payments made in the Republic of Ireland, arguing that [[Legal liability|liability]] in the UK had never been established, whilst in Ireland there had been findings of fault.<ref name=\"Guardian1\" /><ref>{{Cite Hansard|jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Topical Questions |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2009-06-23/debates/b27195ce-b353-48b1-b120-8b64dbd4470d/CommonsChamber |date=June 23, 2009 |volume=494 |column=656 |speaker= Gillian Merron |position= Minister of State at the Department of Health}}</ref> This was found to be incorrect since the basis behind the Irish scheme was compassion, not fault.<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=9 |page=89 |access-date=2010-04-12 |quote=''The payments by the Irish Government were equally made without an admission of liability.''}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII | litigants = R (March) v Secretary of State for Health | link = https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html | court = EWHC | division = Admin | year = 2010 | num = 765 | parallelcite = [2010] 116 BMLR 57 |paras = [27] [30] [34]}}</ref>\n\nThe ministerial decision at the centre of this judicial review hinged on the refusal to adopt a key recommendation of the independent, non-statutory Archer Inquiry.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=19 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote= ''...that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h);''}}</ref> In particular, the Minister rejected Recommendation 6(h), which read as follows: ''\u2033We suggest that payments should be at least the equivalent of those payable under the scheme which applies at any time in Ireland.\u2033''<ref>{{cite report |author=Lord Archer of Sandwell ||authors= |date= 23 February 2009 |title=Independent Public Inquiry Report |url=https://haemophilia.scot/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/76_lord-archer-report.pdf |publisher=Archer Inquiry| chapter=12 |pages=107-110 |access-date=2010-04-11 |quote=''We believe that the following recommendations would help to meet the unmet needs of patients with haemophilia and their families...''}}</ref>\n\n==Judgment==\n\nThe judgement was handed down in Court 49 of the High Court by Mr Justice Holman on Friday, 16th April 2010, the eve of [[World Federation of Hemophilia#World Hemophilia Day|\nWorld Haemophilia Day]] 2010. {{quote box |width=30%|style=min-width:12em|''The thrust of the case on behalf of the claimant is that the answers given by the minister on 23 June and 1 July, when considered separately or cumulatively, reveal a material error of fact on the part of the government as to the situation in Ireland; that that error undermines the reasoning process of the government in their decision to reject recommendation 6 (h); and, accordingly, that the government should be required to reconsider their response to recommendation 6 (h)''.|source=\u2014 Mr Justice Holman<ref name=\"Bailii1\"/>}}\n\n===Material error of fact===\nThe ''March'' case demonstrates that the jurisdiction of the court extends to quashing a decision if the published reasons for the decision contain an error which is considered capable of making a material difference to the outcome of the decision&nbsp;\u2013 had the error in question not been made.<ref>{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |date= June 2011 |title= Administrative Law |edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ |location=Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |page=333 |chapter=9.2.3 |isbn=9780199601752 |quote=''An error of fact revolution?''}}</ref> The sequence of events in Ireland were critical to this case. The Irish government had decided to make payments at a substantial level, very much like compensation, but strictly speaking ''ex gratia'' in nature, and they decided to do this before there was any finding of fault.<ref name=\"Hynes1\" />  It was the Westminster government\u2019s stance on this that propagated the error.\n\nThere are a number of conditions which need to be met in order for the court to intervene: \n{{bulleted list |There must be a demonstrable error to an existing fact;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fordham |first1=Michael |date=July 2012 |chapter=<P49> |title=Judicial Review Handbook |edition=Sixth |location=Oxford |publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |page=511 |isbn=9781849461597 |quote=''But the claimant must demonstrate that (i) there is an error of fact;''}},</ref> |The error needs to be sufficiently established;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.lexology.com/library/document.ashx?g=35c99556-a759-44fe-b12f-94ba54b72469 |title= Quashing a decision on the basis of material error of fact.''|last1= Lidbetter |first1= Andrew |last2= Zar |first2= Nusrat |last3= Condliffe |first3=Anna |publisher= Herbert Smith Freehills LLP|date=30 April 2010 |website=www.lexology.com |access-date=11 April 2020 |quote=...the fact or evidence must have been \u2033established\u2033, in the sense that it was uncontentious and objectively verifiable;}}</ref> | The claimant and their legal advisors must not have been party to the error;<ref>{{cite court |litigants= E v. Secretary of State for the Home Department  |vol=49 |reporter=QB |opinion=1044 |pinpoint=66 |court=EWCA (Civ) |date=2004 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''Thirdly, the appellant (or his advisers) must not been have been responsible for the mistake.''}}</ref> | The error of fact needs to be \u2033material\u2033; in that there could have been an alternative decision \u2033but for the error\u2033.<ref>{{cite court |litigants= R (March) v Secretary of State for Health |vol=765 |reporter=BMLR |opinion=116 |pinpoint=53 |court=EWHC (Admin) |date=2010 |url= https://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2010/765.html |quote=''In my view, the error is material because a different decision might (I stress, might) have been made if the government had correctly focussed on, and grappled with, the compassionate basis of Irish payments, when considering in particular the passage at internal pages 90&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;94 of Archer which underpins recommendation 6 (h).''}}</ref>}}\n\n===Reviewability of Evidence===\nThere was considerable scrutiny over the quality and type of evidence deemed permissible. The use of [[hansard]] was permitted by the court due to specific circumstances relating to the decision under review; in particular, the government\u2019s reasoning behind their decision.  Justice Holman made a clear statement they the court could not to go beyond the scope of reviewability and could not come to any conclusions about the proceedings of Parliament and whether they were in any way inadequate or inaccurate.\n\n==Significance==\nOn the morning the judgment was handed down, the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]] described how he felt the decision was historic for the haemophilia community and how he expected it would be welcomed by the community of some 5,000 people who were infected ''en masse'' with HIV and Hepatitis C through contaminated blood and blood products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/health/8624879.stm |title=Campaigner wins tainted blood case |date=16 April 2010 |website=BBC News |access-date= 2020-04-12}}</ref> Lord Morris went on to expand as follows:\n<blockquote>''\u20261,974 have died in direct consequence of the NHS treatment. Yet until today the legal road to redress was blocked, just as unbreakably as any prospect of securing justice by legislative means. Now with today\u2019s historic breakthrough in the High Court and the huge public backing for my Contaminated Blood Support for Infected and Bereaved Persons Bill, both roads are open. Our determination to ensure that \u2032right is done\u2032 is totally vindicated and a just outcome is now in sight.''<ref>{{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160506174652/http://taintedblood.info/news.php?mode=article&newsid=153 |date=May 6, 2016 |title= Haemophilia Society Welcomes Historic Victory in Court |author= Sue Threakall }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the weeks that followed the quashing of the decision, the government were required by the court to revisit the matter and remake the decision&nbsp;\u2013 ''de novo''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Farrell |first=Anne-Maree |date=2012 |title=The Politics of Blood: Ethics, Innovation and the Regulation of Risk |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HaRqhn75hH8C |location=Cambridge |publisher=Campridge University Press |page=142 |isbn=9780521193184}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Fordham|first=Michael|title=Judicial Review Handbook|publisher=Hart Publishing Ltd. |date=2012|edition=6th|isbn=9781849461597}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clements|first=Richard|title=Public Law\u2014Blackstone\u2032s questions & answers|publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2015|edition=Eighth|isbn=9780198715733}}\n*{{cite book |last= Endicott |first= Timothy |title= Administrative Law |date= 2011|edition=Second |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6YOcAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA333&ots=fISK8plf4X&dq=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=%22R%20(March)%22%20%22error%20of%20fact%22&f=false |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199601752}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Abrogation in Public Law]]\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Public law]]\n[[Category:Common law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom public law]]\n[[Category:Law of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judicial review]]\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReviewability of Evidence:Adding reference.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_(March)_v_Secretary_of_State_for_Health"}
{"title_page": "John Bailey (British actor)", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Bailey\n| image         = British_actor_John_Bailey.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = in ''[[Adam Adamant Lives!]]'' episode ''[[Adam_Adamant_Lives!#Series_1:_1966|The Village of Evil]]'' (1966)\n| birth_name     = John Albert Bailey\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1912|6|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[New Cross]], [[London]], England\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1989|2|18|1912|6|26|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[London]], England\n| occupation     = [[Actor]]\n| othername     = \n| website      = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''John Bailey''' (26 June 1912 \u2013 18 February 1989) was a British screen and TV actor who had a long screen, stage and TV career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/person/2wz/john-bailey|title=John Bailey - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lXnXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=john+bailey+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=E8QUnKKTTn&sig=ACfU3U1kSmckvC3CrYCZz7kkVehm5fQb_g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYxczQ5NfgAhUKRhUIHWPZCXoQ6AEwAnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=john+bailey+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> He was born in South East [[London]].\n\nHe took a number of film roles during the late 1940s and early 1950s which included a sinister role, Stringer, in ''[[High Treason]]''. During the 1960s, he appeared in a number of high-profile BBC TV roles such as in ''[[Doctor Who]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f81ab02|title=John Bailey|website=BFI}}</ref> Most famously, he played the artist Aubrey Green in ''[[The Forsyte Saga]]'' in (1967).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1071033/credits.html|title=BFI Screenonline: Forsyte Saga, The (1967) Credits|website=www.screenonline.org.uk}}</ref> He also took the lead in a highly acclaimed ''[[Wednesday Play]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/TVEpisode.aspx?FilmID=1332&Episode=19650428|title=The Wednesday Play: S|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref>\n\nOne of his notable early films was ''[[High Treason (1951 film)|High Treason]]'' by [[Roy Boulting]] (1951).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6ac4da80|title=High Treason (1951)|website=BFI}}</ref> Set in a tense and austere London during the early [[Cold War]], the tense plot follows the secret services [[MI5]] pursuing a terrorist cell group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/high-treason-v95185|title=High Treason (1951) - Roy Boulting - Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related|website=AllMovie}}</ref> John Bailey's cold and ruthless assassin, Stringer, speaks with a convincing Russian accent. As an actor, he had considerable vocal range, notably employing a clipped, upper class English accent as Inspector Grant in Josephine Tey's ''The Franchise Affair'' (1951). His dark looks and convincing accents led to roles as Italians or [[Eastern Europeans]].\n\nBBC TV's ''[[The Wednesday Play]]'' about [[Sacco and Vanzetti]] (1965) addressed the topical issue of the death penalty. Written by [[Jean Benedetti]] the play was entitled ''[[The Good Shoe Maker and the Poor Fish Pedlar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b720619ff|title=The Good Shoemaker and the Poor Fish Peddler (1965)|website=BFI}}</ref> John Bailey played [[Bartolomeo Vanzetti]], an Italian immigrant in America whose execution was widely regarded as having been a miscarriage of justice.\n\nHe also made various appearances in ''[[Doctor Who]]'', including \"[[The Sensorites]]\" (1964), playing Edward Waterfield in \"[[The Evil of the Daleks]]\" (1967) and \"[[The Horns of Nimon]]\" (1979), as well as appearing in several episodes of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' and as [[Hans Frank]] in the 1978 American television miniseries ''[[Holocaust (TV miniseries)|Holocaust]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3hJJ0hb0GVCvrWHPXbY9NQZ/the-fourth-dimension|title=BBC One - Doctor Who, Season 17, The Horns of Nimon - The Fourth Dimension|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=800|title=John Bailey|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b727edaf3|title=Holocaust (1978)|website=BFI}}</ref>\n \n==Selected filmography==  \n* ''It Happened in Soho'' (1948)\n* ''[[Meet Simon Cherry]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Man on the Run]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Celia (1949 film)|Celia]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Cairo Road (film)|Cairo Road]]'' (1950)\n* ''[[Circle of Danger]]'' (1951) as Pape Llewellyn\n* ''[[The Franchise Affair]]'' (1951) as Inspector Grant\n* ''[[High Treason (1951 film)|High Treason]]'' (1951) as Stringer\n* ''[[Venetian Bird]]'' (1952) as Lieutenant Longo\n* ''[[The Night Won't Talk]]'' (1952) as Clayton Hawkes\n* ''[[So Little Time (film)|So Little Time]]'' (1952)\n* ''[[The Hostage (1956 film)|The Hostage]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Operation Amsterdam]]'' (1959) as an officer\n* ''[[Moment of Danger]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Never Let Go]]'' (1960) as MacKinnon\n* ''[[Rasputin, the Mad Monk]]'' (1966) as the royal physician\n* ''[[Running Scared (1972 film)|Running Scared]]'' (1972) as Inspector\n* ''[[The 14]]'' (1973) as Mr. Sanders\n* ''[[Personal Services]]'' (1987) as Mr. Gardner\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|47318|John Bailey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, John}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n\n\n{{UK-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Bailey\n| image         = British_actor_John_Bailey.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = in ''[[Adam Adamant Lives!]]'' episode ''[[Adam_Adamant_Lives!#Series_1:_1966|The Village of Evil]]'' (1966)\n| birth_name     = John Albert Bailey\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1912|6|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[New Cross]], [[London]], England\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1989|2|18|1912|6|26|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[London]], England\n| occupation     = [[Actor]]\n| othername     = \n| website      = \n| spouse        = \n}}\n'''John Bailey''' (26 June 1912 \u2013 18 February 1989) was a British screen and TV actor who had a long screen, stage and TV career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/person/2wz/john-bailey|title=John Bailey - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lXnXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=john+bailey+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=E8QUnKKTTn&sig=ACfU3U1kSmckvC3CrYCZz7kkVehm5fQb_g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYxczQ5NfgAhUKRhUIHWPZCXoQ6AEwAnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=john+bailey+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> He was born in South East [[London]].\n\nHe took a number of film roles during the late 1940s and early 1950s which included a sinister role, Stringer, in ''[[High Treason]]''. During the 1960s, he appeared in a number of high-profile BBC TV roles such as in ''[[Doctor Who]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f81ab02|title=John Bailey|website=BFI}}</ref> Most famously, he played the artist Aubrey Green in ''[[The Forsyte Saga]]'' in (1967).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1071033/credits.html|title=BFI Screenonline: Forsyte Saga, The (1967) Credits|website=www.screenonline.org.uk}}</ref> He also took the lead in a highly acclaimed ''[[Wednesday Play]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/TVEpisode.aspx?FilmID=1332&Episode=19650428|title=The Wednesday Play: S|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref>\n\nOne of his notable early films was ''[[High Treason (1951 film)|High Treason]]'' by [[Roy Boulting]] (1951).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6ac4da80|title=High Treason (1951)|website=BFI}}</ref> Set in a tense and austere London during the early [[Cold War]], the tense plot follows the secret services [[MI5]] pursuing a terrorist cell group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/high-treason-v95185|title=High Treason (1951) - Roy Boulting - Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related|website=AllMovie}}</ref> John Bailey's cold and ruthless assassin, Stringer, speaks with a convincing Russian accent. As an actor, he had considerable vocal range, notably employing a clipped, upper class English accent as Inspector Grant in Josephine Tey's ''The Franchise Affair'' (1951). His dark looks and convincing accents led to roles as Italians or Eastern Europeans.\n\nBBC TV's ''[[The Wednesday Play]]'' about [[Sacco and Vanzetti]] (1965) addressed the topical issue of the death penalty. Written by [[Jean Benedetti]] the play was entitled ''[[The Good Shoe Maker and the Poor Fish Pedlar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b720619ff|title=The Good Shoemaker and the Poor Fish Peddler (1965)|website=BFI}}</ref> John Bailey played [[Bartolomeo Vanzetti]], an Italian immigrant in America whose execution was widely regarded as having been a miscarriage of justice.\n\nHe also made various appearances in ''[[Doctor Who]]'', including \"[[The Sensorites]]\" (1964), playing Edward Waterfield in \"[[The Evil of the Daleks]]\" (1967) and \"[[The Horns of Nimon]]\" (1979), as well as appearing in several episodes of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' and as [[Hans Frank]] in the 1978 American television miniseries ''[[Holocaust (TV miniseries)|Holocaust]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3hJJ0hb0GVCvrWHPXbY9NQZ/the-fourth-dimension|title=BBC One - Doctor Who, Season 17, The Horns of Nimon - The Fourth Dimension|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=800|title=John Bailey|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b727edaf3|title=Holocaust (1978)|website=BFI}}</ref>\n \n==Selected filmography==  \n* ''It Happened in Soho'' (1948)\n* ''[[Meet Simon Cherry]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Man on the Run]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Celia (1949 film)|Celia]]'' (1949)\n* ''[[Cairo Road (film)|Cairo Road]]'' (1950)\n* ''[[Circle of Danger]]'' (1951) as Pape Llewellyn\n* ''[[The Franchise Affair]]'' (1951) as Inspector Grant\n* ''[[High Treason (1951 film)|High Treason]]'' (1951) as Stringer\n* ''[[Venetian Bird]]'' (1952) as Lieutenant Longo\n* ''[[The Night Won't Talk]]'' (1952) as Clayton Hawkes\n* ''[[So Little Time (film)|So Little Time]]'' (1952)\n* ''[[The Hostage (1956 film)|The Hostage]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Operation Amsterdam]]'' (1959) as an officer\n* ''[[Moment of Danger]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Never Let Go]]'' (1960) as MacKinnon\n* ''[[Rasputin, the Mad Monk]]'' (1966) as the royal physician\n* ''[[Running Scared (1972 film)|Running Scared]]'' (1972) as Inspector\n* ''[[The 14]]'' (1973) as Mr. Sanders\n* ''[[Personal Services]]'' (1987) as Mr. Gardner\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|47318|John Bailey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, John}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n\n\n{{UK-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Peipsi-Pihkva", "label": "safe", "comment": "Eastern Europeans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Bailey_(British_actor)"}
{"title_page": "Tim Dutton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tim Dutton\n| birth_name  = Tim Dutton\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1964}}\n| birth_place  =[[Warwick]], [[Warwickshire]], [[England]]<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1916-2007''</ref>\n| yearsactive = 1991&ndash;present\n| spouse      = \n}}\n\n'''Tim Dutton''' (born 1964) is a British stage, film, and television actor. Dutton's films include ''[[Darkness Falls (1999 film)|Darkness Falls]]'' (1999), ''[[The Bourne Identity (2002 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'' (2002), [[The Infiltrator (2016 film)|The Infiltrator]] (2016) and ''[[The Detonator]]''. He starred in the Academy Award and BAFTA nominated movie ''[[Tom & Viv (film)|Tom & Viv]]'' (1994) as Maurice Haigh-Wood.\n\nHe grew up in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Warwickshire]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tim has a secret crush |url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/local-news/tim-has-a-secret-crush-3117716 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |work=Coventry Telegraph |date=25 January 2007}}</ref> He read [[Law]] at [[Wolverhampton University]] and gained an [[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]] (Hons) before turning to acting.\n\nDutton played Mark Owens in ''[[Soldier, Soldier]]'', Donna Tucker's tutor and lover (4 episodes, 1994). He had a recurring role in the Fox television series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' as Brian Selig, a love interest of Calista Flockhart\u2019s title character. He also starred in the short-lived but critically acclaimed CBS sitcom about the [[Pilgrims (Plymouth Colony)|Pilgrims]] in [[Plymouth Colony]], ''[[Thanks (TV series)|Thanks]]'' which [[Entertainment Weekly]] called \"the funniest new sitcom of the [1999\u20132000] season.\"  He made an appearance in the ''[[Press Gang]]'' episode \"Chance is a Fine Thing\" as Clark Kent, Judy's jealous boyfriend. He has worked twice with the writer [[Alan Bleasdale]], starring in ''Melissa'' with Jenifer Ehle (1997) and ''Oliver Twist'' (1999). In 2001 he starred in the ABC comedy pilot ''H.M.O.'' with [[John Cleese]], playing two ex-pat surgeons in a LA hospital. \nIn 2010 he produced and starred in ''The Rendezvous''.\nHe has twice starred with the  actress, Tara Fitzgerald, in director [[Ferdinand Fairfax]]'s ''Frenchman\u2019s Creek'' (1998) and ''In the Name of Love'' (1999).\n\nHis Theatre credits include plays in the West End (London Assurance), Chichester Festival Theatre (Loves Labour\u2019s Lost, Victory), The Royal Exchange Manchester (She\u2019s in Your Hands), twice working with director Sam Mendes.\n\nDutton made a major stage appearance in 2014 in [[Headlong (theatre company)|Headlong]]'s highly acclaimed production of 1984 directed by [[Robert Icke]], at the Almeida and later in the West End and Internationally. He played the false friend and Party apparatchik, [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Brien]].{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} For which he won Best Featured Actor, [[BroadwayWorld|Broadway World, Los Angeles Awards]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1991|| ''A Murder of Quality'' || Simon Snow || TV movie\n|-\n|1992|| ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]'' || Constable ||\n|-\n|1994|| ''[[Tom & Viv (film)|Tom & Viv]]'' || Maurice Haigh-Wood ||\n|-\n|1997|| ''[[Into Thin Air: Death on Everest]]'' || Andy Harris || TV movie\n|-\n|1998|| ''Hard to Forget'' || Max Warner || TV movie\n|-\n|1998|| ''[[St. Ives (1998 film)|St. Ives]]'' || Fran\u00e7ois ||\n|-\n|1999|| ''[[Darkness Falls (1999 film)|Darkness Falls]]'' || Mark Driscoll ||\n|-\n|2001|| ''Dead by Monday'' || Alex Hiller ||\n|-\n|2002|| ''[[The Bourne Identity (2002 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'' || Eamon ||\n|-\n|2004|| ''Tooth'' || Dad ||\n|-\n|2004|| ''[[The Queen of Sheba's Pearls]]'' || Father Talbot ||\n|-\n|2005|| ''Terminal'' || Mike ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''Bye Bye Harry!'' || Stuart ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''The Detonator'' || Josef Bostanescu ||\n|-\n|2010|| ''The Rendezvous'' || Michael ||\n|-\n|2013|| ''Delight'' || Gregor ||\n|-\n|2016|| ''[[The Infiltrator (2016 film)|The Infiltrator]]'' || Ian Howard ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0244957|name=Tim Dutton}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutton, Tim}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n{{UK-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tim Dutton\n| birth_name  = Tim Dutton\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1964}}\n| birth_place  =[[Warwick]], [[Warwickshire]], [[England]]<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1916-2007''</ref>\n| yearsactive = 1991&ndash;present\n| spouse      = \n}}\n\n'''Tim Dutton''' (born 1964) is a British stage, film, and television actor. Dutton's films include ''[[Darkness Falls (1999 film)|Darkness Falls]]'' (1999), ''[[The Bourne Identity (2002 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'' (2002), [[The Infiltrator (2016 film)|The Infiltrator]] (2016) and ''[[The Detonator]]''. He starred in the Academy Award and BAFTA nominated movie ''[[Tom & Viv (film)|Tom & Viv]]'' (1994) as Maurice Haigh-Wood.\n\nHe grew up in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]], [[Warwickshire]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tim has a secret crush |url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/local-news/tim-has-a-secret-crush-3117716 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |work=Coventry Telegraph |date=25 January 2007}}</ref> He read [[Law]] at [[Wolverhampton University]] and gained an [[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]] (Hons) before turning to acting.\n\nDutton played Mark Owens in ''[[Soldier, Soldier]]'', Donna Tucker's tutor and lover (4 episodes, 1994). He had a recurring role in the Fox television series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' as Brian Selig, a love interest of Calista Flockhart\u2019s title character. He also starred in the short-lived but critically acclaimed CBS sitcom about the [[Pilgrims (Plymouth Colony)|Pilgrims]] in [[Plymouth Colony]], ''[[Thanks (TV series)|Thanks]]'' which [[Entertainment Weekly]] called \"the funniest new sitcom of the [1999\u20132000] season.\"  He made an appearance in the ''[[Press Gang]]'' episode \"Chance is a Fine Thing\" as Clark Kent, Judy's jealous boyfriend. He has worked twice with the writer [[Alan Bleasdale]], starring in ''Melissa'' with Jenifer Ehle (1997) and ''Oliver Twist'' (1999). In 2001 he starred in the ABC comedy pilot ''H.M.O.'' with [[John Cleese]], playing two ex-pat surgeons in a LA hospital. \nIn 2010 he produced and starred in ''The Rendezvous''.\nHe has twice starred with the  actress, Tara Fitzgerald, in director [[Ferdinand Fairfax]]'s ''Frenchman\u2019s Creek'' (1998) and ''In the Name of Love'' (1999).\n\nHis Theatre credits include plays in the West End (London Assurance), Chichester Festival Theatre (Loves Labour\u2019s Lost, Victory), The Royal Exchange Manchester (She\u2019s in Your Hands), twice working with director Sam Mendes.\n\nDutton made a major stage appearance in 2014 in [[Headlong (theatre company)|Headlong]]'s highly acclaimed production of 1984 directed by [[Robert Icke]], at the Almeida and later in the West End and Internationally. He played the false friend and Party apparatchik, [[O'Brien (1984)|O'Brien]].{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} For which he won Best Featured Actor, [[Broadway World, Los Angeles Awards]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1991|| ''A Murder of Quality'' || Simon Snow || TV movie\n|-\n|1992|| ''[[Patriot Games (film)|Patriot Games]]'' || Constable ||\n|-\n|1994|| ''[[Tom & Viv (film)|Tom & Viv]]'' || Maurice Haigh-Wood ||\n|-\n|1997|| ''[[Into Thin Air: Death on Everest]]'' || Andy Harris || TV movie\n|-\n|1998|| ''Hard to Forget'' || Max Warner || TV movie\n|-\n|1998|| ''[[St. Ives (1998 film)|St. Ives]]'' || Fran\u00e7ois ||\n|-\n|1999|| ''[[Darkness Falls (1999 film)|Darkness Falls]]'' || Mark Driscoll ||\n|-\n|2001|| ''Dead by Monday'' || Alex Hiller ||\n|-\n|2002|| ''[[The Bourne Identity (2002 film)|The Bourne Identity]]'' || Eamon ||\n|-\n|2004|| ''Tooth'' || Dad ||\n|-\n|2004|| ''[[The Queen of Sheba's Pearls]]'' || Father Talbot ||\n|-\n|2005|| ''Terminal'' || Mike ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''Bye Bye Harry!'' || Stuart ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''The Detonator'' || Josef Bostanescu ||\n|-\n|2010|| ''The Rendezvous'' || Michael ||\n|-\n|2013|| ''Delight'' || Gregor ||\n|-\n|2016|| ''[[The Infiltrator (2016 film)|The Infiltrator]]'' || Ian Howard ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0244957|name=Tim Dutton}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutton, Tim}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stratford-upon-Avon]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n{{UK-screen-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Drmd78978900", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link created", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Dutton"}
{"title_page": "1510 Influenza pandemic", "text_new": "[[File:1500 map by Juan de la Cosa-North up.jpg|thumb|499x499px|The 1510 flu pandemic was the first to be chronicled across continents.]]\n\nIn 1510 an acute respiratory disease emerged in Asia<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> before spreading through [[North Africa]] and [[Europe]] during the first chronicled, inter-regional [[Influenza pandemic|flu pandemic]] generally recognized by medical historians and epidemiologists.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ghendon|first=Youri|date=1994|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza through History on|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3520976?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents|journal=European Journal of Epidemiology|volume=10|pages=451-453|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref name=\"500th\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David|last2=Taubengerger|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Folkers|first3=Gregory|last4=Fauci|first4=Anthony|date=15 December 2010|title=Pandemic Influenza\u2019s 500th Anniversary|script-title=|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3106245/|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=51|pages=1442-1444|via=Silverchair}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=FORBES|first=JOHN|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7OQEAAAAQAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA108&dq=Coqueluche+in+France+1510&hl=en|title=THE BRITISH AND FOREIGN MEDICAL REVIEW OF QUARTERLY JOURNAL OF PRACTICAL MEDICINE AND SURGERY|date=1839|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=108|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David M.|last2=Taubenberger|first2=Jeffery K.|date=27 June 2011|title=Pandemic influenza: certain uncertainties|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3246071/|journal=Reviews in medical virology|volume=21|issue=5|pages=262\u2013284|doi=10.1002/rmv.689|issn=1052-9276|pmc=3246071|pmid=21706672|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> Influenza-like illnesses had been documented in Europe since at least [[Charlemagne]],<ref name=\":02\" /> with 1357's outbreak the first to be called ''influenza'',<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> but the 1510 flu pandemic is the first to be pathologically described<ref>{{Cite book|last=Riverside|first=Clifford E. Trafzer, University of California|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1QJN9xo3JUC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA109&dq=flu+of+1510&hl=en|title=Forgotten Voices: Death Records of the Yakama, 1888-1964|last2=McCoy|first2=Robert R.|date=2009-03-20|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8108-6648-5|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=109|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/11/101112141130.htm|title=Scientists explore 1510 influenza pandemic and lessons learned|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> following communication advances brought about by the [[printing press]]. Flu became more widely referred to as ''coqueluche'' and ''coccolucio'' in [[Kingdom of France|France]] and [[Kingdom of Sicily|Sicily]] during this epidemic,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N6FLAAAAYAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA332&dq=L'epidemie+de+1510+mezeray&hl=en|title=Dictionnaire encyclop\u00e9dique des sciences m\u00e9dicales|date=1877|publisher=Asselin|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=332|language=fr}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> variations of which became the most popular names for flu in [[early modern Europe]].<ref name=\":02\" /> The pandemic caused significant disruption in government, church, and society<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\"500th\" /> with near-universal infection<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=SCHWEICH|first=Heinrich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z_hZAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=die+epidemie+die+jahres+1510&hl=en|title=Die Influenza. Ein historischer und \u00e4tiologischer Versuch ... Mit einer Vorrede von ... J. F. C. Hecker|last2=HECKER|first2=Justus Friedrich Carl|date=1836|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=57|language=de}}</ref> and a mortality rate of around 1%.<ref name=\":02\" /> \n\n== Asia ==\nThe 1510 flu is suspected of originating in East Asia,<ref name=\":02\" /> possibly [[China]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Gregor Horst asserts in ''Operum Medicorum tombs primus'' (1661) that the disease came from the Asia and spread along trade routes<ref name=\":02\" /> before attacking the Middle East and North Africa. German medical writer [[Justus Hecker]] suggested the 1510 influenza most likely came from Asia because of the historical nature of other influenza viruses to originate there in more recent pandemics.\n[[File:Eastern Mediterranean and Aegean Sea. Battista Agnese, PORTOLAN ATLAS (Italy ca. 1550).jpg|thumb|353x353px|Influenza had spread in North Africa before arriving in Europe.]]\n\n=== Middle East ===\nThe flu spread along trade routes towards North Africa,<ref name=\":02\" /> traveling southwest through the Middle East. Frequently visited cities like [[Jerusalem]] and [[Mecca]] would have almost certainly been reached by the flu, with large volumes of people destined to travel to [[Egypt]], North Africa, and the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\n== Africa ==\nIt is generally understood that the 1510 influenza had spread in Africa before Europe.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> Influenza was likely across North Africa before crossing continents through the Mediterranean, arriving in [[Malta]]<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Stedman|first=Thomas Lathrop|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=DqEwAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&pg=GBS.PA11|title=Twentieth Century Practice: Infectious diseases|date=1898|publisher=W. Wood|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=11|language=en}}</ref> where British historian [[Thomas Vowler Short]] believes the \"island of ''Melite'' in ''Africa''\" became the 1510 flu's springboard into Europe.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /> <br />\n[[File:General map of Malta.svg|thumb|146x146px|The disease came to Malta on crews infected in Africa.|left]]\n== Europe ==\nEurope's internationally-traveled cities and flu's highly contagious nature enabled its spread through European populations. The 1510 flu disrupted royal courts, church services, and social life across Europe. Contemporary chroniclers and those who've read their accounts observed how entire populations were attacked at once,<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> which is how the disease first received the name ''influenza'' (from the belief that such outbreaks were caused by influences like stars or cold).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=A. Mir|first=Shakil|date=December 2009|title=History of Swine Flu|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/774f5d6553eeae3107b5b114f055b64f/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=54966|journal=JK Science|publisher=PG Department of Pharmacology, Govt Medical College, Srinagar|volume=8|pages=163|via=ProQuest}}</ref> [[Turin]] professor Francisco Vallerioli (aka Valleriola) writes that the 1510 flu featured \"Constriction of breathing, and beginning with a hoarseness of voice and... shivering. Not long after that there being a cooked humor which fills the lungs.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Physicians like Valleriola described the 1510 flu as more fatal to children<ref>{{Cite book|last=Vaughan|first=Warren Taylor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lhc6AQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Influenza: An Epidemiologic Study|date=1921|publisher=American journal of hygiene|year=|isbn=|location=Baltimore, Maryland|pages=157|language=en}}</ref> and those who were bled.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />  Lawyer Francesco Muralto noted that \"the disease killed 10 people out of a thousand in one day,\" supporting a fatality rate of around 1%.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Sicily and the Italian Kingdoms ===\n[[File:Italy map 1584.jpg|thumb|Flu arrived in Sicily from [[Malta]], and quickly spread along the Italian coast.]]\nThe first cases of influenza began to appear in [[Sicily]] around July<ref name= Alibrandi>{{cite journal|last=Alibrandi|first=Rosamaria|title=When early modern Europe caught the flu. A scientific account of pandemic influenza in sixteenth century Sicily|journal=Medicina Historica|volume=2|pages=19-25}}</ref> after the arrival of infected merchant ships from [[Malta]].<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Parkin|first=John|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=9RcDAAAAQAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA35|title=Epidemiology; or, The remote cause of epidemic diseases in the animal and in the vegetable creation|date=1880|publisher=J. and A. Churchill|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xbo0AQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA220&dq=La+coqueluche+de+1510&hl=en|title=Dictionnaire encyclop\u00e9dique des sciences m\u00e9dicales: publi\u00e9 sous la direction de MM. les docteurs Raige-Delorme et A. Dechambre|date=1882|publisher=P. Asselin, S' de Lab\u00e9, V. Masson et fils|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=220|language=fr}}</ref> In Sicily it was commonly called ''coccolucio'' for the hoods the sick often wore over their heads.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Potter|first=C. W.|date=2001|title=A history of influenza|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1365-2672.2001.01492.x|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=91|issue=4|pages=572\u2013579|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2672.2001.01492.x|issn=1365-2672}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beveridge|first=W.I.B|date=1991|title=The Chronicle of Influenza Epidemics|url=|journal=History and Philosophy of the Life Sciences|volume=13|pages=223-234|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref name=\"catarrhal\">{{cite book|last=Thomson|first=Theophilus|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Annals_of_Influenza_Or_Epidemic_Catarrha/INc0AQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1|title=Annals of Influenza or Epidemic Catarrhal Fever in Great Britain|date=1852|publisher=The Sydenham Society Instituted|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=3-4|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Influenza quickly spread out along the Mediterranean coasts of Italy and southern France<ref name=Alibrandi/> via merchant ships leaving the island.  \n\nIn [[Emilia-Romagna]], Tommasino de' Bianchi recorded the recovery of [[Modena|Modena's]] first cases on 13 July 1510, writing that in the city \"there appears an illness that lasts three days with a great fever, and headache and then they rise .. but there remains a terrible cough that lasts maybe eight days, and then they recover.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David|last2=North|first2=Michael|last3=Taubenberger|first3=Jeffrey|date=4 December 2011|title=Eyewitness accounts of the 1510 influenza pandemic in Europe|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2810%2962204-0|journal=Lancet|volume=367|pages=1894-1895|via=The Lancet}}</ref> This data would indicate that the first cases flu, which has an incubation period of one to four days, began to fall ill in the Emilia-Romagna region around late June or early July. In [[Bologna]] an 8 year-old named Ugo Bancopagni, who would later become [[Pope Gregory XIII]], became gravely ill with flu but recovered without permanent complications.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n[[Pope Julius II]] attributed the outbreaks in [[Rome]] and the [[Holy See]] to God's wrath.<ref name=\":02\" /> [[Pope Gregory XIII]] would later blame the 1510 influenza in France on the resistance of [[Louis XII of France|King Louis XII]] to divine authority.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n=== Central Europe ===\n[[File:Achilles Pirminius Gasser.JPG|thumb|Achilles Gasser mentions an epidemic of \"catarrhal fever\" in upper Germany.<ref name=\":9\" />|alt=|259x259px]]\nFlu spread over the Alps into Switzerland and the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. In Switzerland it is documented as being called ''das Gruppie'' by the [[Mellingen]] chronicler Anton Tegenfeld,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Karsten|first=Gustaf|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Journal_of_English_and_Germanic_Phil/VF-qD7s4txoC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=1510+flu+england&pg=PA513&printsec=frontcover|title=The Journal of English and German Philology|publisher=University of Illinois, Urbana-Champagne|year=1920|isbn=|location=Urbana-Champagne|pages=513}}</ref> the flu nickname then preferred by German-speaking Europeans. A respiratory illness seemed to have menaced the Canton of Aargua in June, with the population falling ill with sniffling, coughing, and fatigue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Schindler|first=Wolfgang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3OetxIToFvIC&pg=PA344&lpg=PA344&dq=das+gruppie+1510+coqueluche&source=bl&ots=Pm2gpmJIuQ&sig=ACfU3U13GMtsaGUKj9hWLJ4UB3gO0CSjLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjs-rq618LoAhUWpp4KHYQ4CFAQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=das%20gruppie%201510%20coqueluche&f=false|title=Grippe, Kamm und Eulenspiegel: Festschrift f\u00fcr Elmar Seebold zum 65. Geburtstag|last2=Untermann|first2=J\u00fcrgen|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=1999|isbn=978-3-11-015617-1|location=|pages=244|language=de}}</ref> German physician [[Achilles Gasser]] records a deadly epidemic spreading over the Holy Roman Empire's upper Kingdoms, branching into the cities and the \"whole mankind:\" ''Mira qua edam Epidemia mortales per urbes hanc totamque adeo superiorem Germaniam corripiebat, qua aegri IV vel V ad summum dies molestissimis destillationibus laborabant ac ration privati instar phrenicorum furebant, atque inde iterum convalescebant, paucissimis ad Gorcum demissis.''<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nAndr\u00e9 de Burgo's letters dated 24 August 1510 indicate [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Austria]] had to intervene at a royal assembly between her father, [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I]], and [[Louis XII of France]] because the King of France was too sick with \"coqueluche\" to be spoken to.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Louis|first=X. I. I.|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=7b2c3BKPPVgC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA287|title=Lettres du roi Louis XII et du cardinal Georges d'Amboise: depuis 1504 \u00e0 1514|last2=Godefroy|date=1712|publisher=Foppens|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=287-288|language=fr}}</ref> Influenza spread out from the Holy Roman Empire towards Northern Europe, the [[Baltic states]],<ref name=\":11\" /> and west towards [[Kingdom of France|France]] and [[Kingdom of England|England]].<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:France XVe si\u00e8cl2e.jpg|thumb|It quickly spread to France's southern port cities first, then westward from the Alps to Paris.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />|left]]\nArriving aboard infected sailors from Sicily, influenza struck the [[Kingdom of France]] through the ports of [[Marseille]] and [[Nice]] and spread through the international crowds of the shipyards. It was referred to as ''cephalie catarrhal'' or more commonly ''coqueluche''.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Katona|first=Mihaly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CapNAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Abhandlung \u00fcber die Grippe (Influenza) in Wien in dem Jahre 1833|date=1833|publisher=Edl. v. Schmid|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=25-27|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Desruelles|first=Henry-Marie-Joseph|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Go9fAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA22&dq=coqueluche+de+1510&hl=en|title=Traite De La Coqueluche, d'apres les Principes de la Doctrine Physiologique|publisher=J. B. Bailliere|year=1827|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=22|language=fr}}</ref> [[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray|M\u00e9zeray]] traces the etymology of ''coqueluche'' to the 1410s<ref name=\":5\" /> when sufferers would wear bonnets resembling coqueluchons, a kind of monk's cowl. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyen|first=Guillaume Le|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=wz5wdUawOpoC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PP1|title=Annalles et chronicques du pais de Laval et parties circonvoisines depuis l'an de Nostre Seigneur Ihesu-Crist 1480 jusq\u00fa \u00e0 l'ann\u00e9e 1537, avec un pr\u00e9ambule retrospectif du temps anticque jadis|date=1857|publisher=H. Godbert|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=134|language=fr}}</ref>French surgeon [[Ambroise Par\u00e9]] describes the outbreak as having been a \"rheumatic affliction of the head...with constriction of the heart and lungs.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Merchants, pilgrims, and other travelers from the south and east spread the virus throughout the western Mediterranean in July.<ref name=\":4\" /> By August it had appear in [[Tours]] and rapidly propagated itself throughout France, sickening the entire country by September.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Corradi|first=Alfonso|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EMFdvvQlL4AC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA20&dq=Influenza+de+1510+spain&hl=en|title=Annali delle epidemie occorse in Italia dalle prime memorie fino al 1850 scritti da Alfonso Corradi: Dal 1501 a tutto il 1600 con una tavola delle cose piu memorabili si della 1. che della 2. parte|date=1867|publisher=Tipi Gamberini e Parmeggiani|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=19|language=it}}</ref> French poet and historian Jean Bouchet, employed by King Louis XII's Royal Court, wrote that the epidemic \"appeared in the entire Kingdom of France, as much in the towns as in the countryside.\"<ref name=\":02\" />  \n\n''Coqueluche'' filled up the hospitals in France.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/La_Revue_mondiale/Ze3I8lnlJAQC?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=l%27epidemie+de+1510&dq=l%27epidemie+de+1510&printsec=frontcover|title=La Revue Mondial|publisher=Harvard University|year=1919|isbn=|location=Cambridge, MA|pages=262}}</ref> King Louis XII's National Assembly of [[Bishop|Bishops]], [[Prelate|Prelates]], and university [[Professor|professors]] scheduled for September 1510 was delayed because of the intensity of the flu in [[Paris]]. <ref name=\"500th\" /> [[Jean Fernel]] (aka Fernelius), physician to [[Henry III of France]], compares the 1557 influenza to the 1510 epidemic which attacked everyone with fever, a heaviness in their head, and profound coughing.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=DqEwAAAAIAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA11|title=Twentieth Century Practice: An International Encyclopedia of Modern Medical Science by Leading Authors of Europe and America|publisher=W. Wood|year=1898|isbn=|editor-last=Stedman|editor-first=Thomas|volume=15|location=New York|pages=11}}</ref> Up to 1000 Parisians per day were dying at the height of the \"1510 peste.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7yzFlQ-YzTsC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=1000+personnes+chaque+jour+peste+1510&hl=en|title=Quintessence de l'\u00e9conomie politique transcendante \u00e0 l'usage des \u00e9lecteurs et des philosophes par le baron de M\u00fcnster|date=1842|publisher=Dutertre|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=72|language=fr}}</ref> French historian [[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray|Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zery]] mentions that it disrupted judicial proceeding and colleges,<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> and that the 1510 flu was more widespread and deadly in France than in other countries.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bergeron|first=Georges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i_--syugmU8C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Des Caract\u00e8rs G\u00e9n\u00e9raux des Affections Catarrhals Aigues|date=1874|publisher=A. Delahaye|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=35|language=fr}}</ref>\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray.jpg|thumb|[[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray]] had access to original documents describing the influenza of 1510.<ref name=\":02\" />]]\n\n[[Georges d'Amboise|Cardinal Georges d'Amboise]], a close friend and advisor to the King of France, is sometimes believed to have died of influenza since his health sharply declined after arriving in Lyons in May 1510.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Thomas|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=XstBAAAAcAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA612|title=The History of France: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time|date=1856|publisher=London Print. and Publishing Company|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=A.D. 1510|language=en}}</ref>  The cardinal, also known as Monseigneur le Ledat, made his final testimony and recited [[Sacraments of the Catholic Church|Sacraments]] around May 22<ref>{{Cite book|last=Louis|first=X. I. I.|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=7b2c3BKPPVgC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA233|title=Lettres du roi Louis XII et du cardinal Georges d'Amboise: depuis 1504 \u00e0 1514|last2=Godefroy|date=1712|publisher=Foppens|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=233|language=fr}}</ref> before he died on the 25. His sudden decline in health and flu's arrival in Europe around early summer have created uncertainty as to whether he died of gout or influenza, but \"coqueluche\" is not mentioned in French royal correspondence that year until August.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== England and Ireland ===\nBritish medical historian [[Charles Creighton]] claims there is one foreign account of the 1510 flu in England,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|last=Creighton|first=Charles|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=CyoJAAAAIAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA399|title=A History of Epidemics in Britain ...|date=1891|publisher=The University Press|year=|isbn=|location=Cambridge, UK|pages=399-400|language=en}}</ref> but does not elaborate.<ref name=\":11\" /> An epidemiological study of past influenza pandemics reviewing previous medical historians has found England was affected in 1510.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x7SJoXpeUrAC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=The American Journal of Hygiene: Monographic series|date=1921|publisher=Johns Hopkins Press|year=|isbn=|location=John Hopkins University|pages=7|language=en}}</ref> [[Jean Fernel|Fernel]] and [[Ambroise Par\u00e9|Par\u00e9]] suggest that the 1510 influenza \"spread to almost all countries of the world, except the New World.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> There were reports of symptoms like \"gastrodynia\" and noteworthy murrain among cattle.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kilbourne|first=E. D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybkpBgAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA6&dq=1510+influenza&hl=en|title=Influenza|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-1-4684-5239-6|location=New York|pages=6|language=en}}</ref> The 1510 flu is also recorded to have reached [[Ireland]].<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Spain and Portugal ===\n[[File:UBBasel Map 1500-1599 Kartenslg AA 131.tif|thumb|left|Influenza spread to [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]] around the same time it reached the Alps.|302x302px]]\nInfluenza reached the [[Iberian Peninsula]] early after Italy, due to the highly interconnected trade and pilgrimage routes between Spain, Portugal, and the Italian kingdoms. Cases began to appear in Portugal around the same time the disease entered the Holy Roman Empire.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /> Spanish cities were reportedly \"dispopulated\" by the 1510 flu.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|last=Ryan|first=Jeffrey R.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA16&dq=spanish+cities+were+dispopulated&hl=en|title=Pandemic Influenza: Emergency Planning and Community Preparedness|date=2008-08-01|publisher=CRC Press|year=|isbn=978-1-4200-6088-1|location=|pages=16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The Americas ==\n[[File:Hispaniola Vinckeboons4.jpg|thumb|Influenza previously attacked the [[Island of Santo Domingo]] in 1493 with severe consequences. |322x322px]]\nThere are no records of influenza affecting the [[New World]] in 1510,<ref name=\":02\" /> even though numerous other European powers like France, England, and Portugal were sending their first fleets of ships to the [[New World]] after [[Spain]]. Influenza had previously afflicted the Isle of Santo Domingo (now [[Hispaniola]]) in [[1493]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guerre, M.D.|first=Francisco|date=Fall 1988|title=The Earliest American Epidemic: The Influenza of 1493|url=|journal=Social Science History|volume=12|pages=305-325|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n\n== Medicine and Treatment ==\nBlistering on the back of the head and shoulders was one form of treatment prescribed in Europe for the flu.<ref name=\":02\" /> [[Ambroise Par\u00e9|Par\u00e9]] regarded the common treatments of [[bloodletting]] and [[purgation]] to be especially dangerous to 1510's flu patients.<ref name=\":02\" /> Supraorbital pain and vision problems were symptoms<ref name=\":13\" /> of ''coqueluche'', so sufferers may have felt tempted to wear hoods due to light sensitivity. [[Thomas Vowler Short|Short]] describes some medicinal treatments for the 1510 flu including \"Bole Armoniac, oily lintus, pectoral troches, and decoctions.\"<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />\n\n== Origin of 1510 Influenza ==\n[[Justus Friedrich Carl Hecker|Justus Hecker]] and John Parkin presume the 1510 influenza originated from East Asia because of the historical nature of other influenzas originating from said region,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|last=Hecker|first=Justus Friedrich Carl|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xf5CAQAAIAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=1510&hl=en|title=The epidemics of the middle ages|last2=Babington|first2=Benjamin Guy|date=1859|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner & co.|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=202-205|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gordon|first=Sir Charles Alexander|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KC0AAAAAQAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA348&dq=history+of+epidemics+in+china+1510&hl=en|title=An Epitome of the Reports of the Medical Officers to the Chinese Imperial Maritime Customs Service, from 1871 to 1882: With Chapters on the History of Medicine in China, Materia Medica, Epidemics, Famine, Ethnology, and Chronology in Relation to Medicine and Public Health|date=1884|publisher=Bailli\u00e8re, Tindall, and Cox|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=348|language=en}}</ref> while Gregor Horst documented that the 1510 flu spread along trade routes from East Asia to Africa before reaching Europe in 1661.<ref name=\":02\" /> Influenza viruses sometimes leap from Asia's migratory water fowl after massive migrations congregate near water sources for humans and domesticated animals (which can function as a cross-species catalysts for creating new strains of pandemic flu).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ma|first=Wenjun|last2=Kahn|first2=Robert E|last3=Richt|first3=Juergen A|date=2008-11-27|title=The pig as a mixing vessel for influenza viruses: Human and veterinary implications|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2702078/|journal=Journal of molecular and genetic medicine : an international journal of biomedical research|volume=3|issue=1|pages=158\u2013166|issn=1747-0862|pmc=2702078|pmid=19565018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/MPH-Modules/PH/PH709_Influenza/PH709_Influenza4.html|title=The Origin of New Flu Strains|website=sphweb.bumc.bu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> European chroniclers noticed that the 1510 influenza did appear in North Africa before Europe, which has lead some medical historians to suggest it may have developed there<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Bray|first=R. S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRHbDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA196&dq=1510+influenza+pandemic+asia&hl=en&source=newbks_fb#v=onepage&q=1510%20influenza%20pandemic%20asia&f=false|title=Armies of Pestilence: The Impact of Disease on History|date=|publisher=ISD LLC|year=1996|isbn=978-0-7188-4816-3|location=Cambridge, England|pages=196-197|language=en}}</ref>(parts of [[North Africa]] also lie along migratory bird ways, specifically the east Africa-West Asia and Black Sea-Mediterranean routes, that make it vulnerable to spontaneous reassortment of pandemic flu viruses).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baghi|first=Hossein Bannazadeh|last2=Soroush|first2=Mohammad Hossein|date=2018-05-01|title=Influenza: the role of the Middle East and north Africa?|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(18)30213-5/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=18|issue=5|pages=498|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(18)30213-5|issn=1473-3099|pmid=29695361}}</ref> But there remains no chronicled or biological evidence to suggest the 1510 flu originated from, as opposed to just spread in, Africa before reaching Europe.   \n\n== Debunking Suggestions of Whooping Cough ==\nThe 1510 ''coqueluche'' has been recognized as influenza by modern epidemiologists<ref name=\"500th\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> and medical historians.<ref name=\":11\" /> Suggestions that the 1510 ''coqueluche'' was [[whooping cough]] have been doubted<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lB5KAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA3&dq=whooping+cough+epidemics&hl=en|title=Whooping Cough: Essential Facts Concerning Whooping Cough, Its Prevention and Treatment with Appropriate Vaccines|date=1920|publisher=Eli Lilly & Company|year=|isbn=|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> because adult sufferers often experienced \"precipitous\"<ref name=\":02\" /> symptoms described by contemporaries like Thomasino de Bianchi<ref name=\":02\" /> or Valleriola as high fever for 3 days, headache, prostration, loss of sleep and appetite, delirium,<ref name=\":7\" /> a cough most severe on the 5th to 10th days, <ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P9dNAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA542&dq=coqueluche+of+1510&hl=en|title=Encyclopedia of Practical Medicine: Variolla, Vaccination, Vericella, Cholera, Erysipelas, Whooping Cough, Hay Fever|date=1902|publisher=Saunders|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=542|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 21, 1918|editor-last=Stedman|editor-first=Thomas|title=Paris Epidemics of the XVI Century|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Medical_Record/Kt0yAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=coqueluche+of+1510+whooping+cough&pg=PA1076&printsec=frontcover|journal=Medical Record: A Weekly Journal of Medicine and Surgery|publisher=M.M. Wood & Co.|volume=94|pages=1076|via=}}</ref> lung congestion,<ref name=\":02\" /> and slow recovery beginning on the second week.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":14\" />Adults with pertussis will usually cough for weeks before becoming gradually more ill then recovering over a period of months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foundation.chestnet.org/patient-education-resources/pertussis/|title=Pertussis|website=CHEST Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IcQkAQAAIAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA120&dq=holland+whooping+cough+epidemic+1746&hl=en|title=American Association for the Study and Prevention of Infant Mortality: Transactions of the Annual Meeting - Milwaukee, October 19-21, 1916|publisher=Franklin Printing Company|year=1917|isbn=|location=Baltimore|pages=126|language=en}}</ref> The ''coqueluche'' of 1510 is considered to be influenza by most experts, from modern epidemiologists<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\"500th\" /> to medical historians<ref name=\":11\" /> due to its sudden onset of symptoms, explosive spread over Europe,<ref name=\":10\" /> and timelines of sickness to recovery. The first outbreak of whooping cough to be agreed on by most medical historians is [[Guillaume de Baillou|Guillaume de Baillou's]] description of an outbreak in Paris in [[1578]].<ref name=\":8\" />  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Influenza pandemics]]\n[[Category:Global health]]\n[[Category:Epidemics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:1500 map by Juan de la Cosa-North up.jpg|thumb|499x499px|The 1510 flu pandemic was the first to be chronicled across continents.]]\n\nIn 1510 an acute respiratory disease emerged in Asia<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> before spreading through [[North Africa]] and [[Europe]] during the first chronicled, inter-regional [[Influenza pandemic|flu pandemic]] generally recognized by medical historians and epidemiologists.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ghendon|first=Youri|date=1994|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza through History on|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/3520976?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents|journal=European Journal of Epidemiology|volume=10|pages=451-453|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref name=\"500th\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David|last2=Taubengerger|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Folkers|first3=Gregory|last4=Fauci|first4=Anthony|date=15 December 2010|title=Pandemic Influenza\u2019s 500th Anniversary|script-title=|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3106245/|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|volume=51|pages=1442-1444|via=Silverchair}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=FORBES|first=JOHN|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7OQEAAAAQAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA108&dq=Coqueluche+in+France+1510&hl=en|title=THE BRITISH AND FOREIGN MEDICAL REVIEW OF QUARTERLY JOURNAL OF PRACTICAL MEDICINE AND SURGERY|date=1839|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=108|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David M.|last2=Taubenberger|first2=Jeffery K.|date=27 June 2011|title=Pandemic influenza: certain uncertainties|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3246071/|journal=Reviews in medical virology|volume=21|issue=5|pages=262\u2013284|doi=10.1002/rmv.689|issn=1052-9276|pmc=3246071|pmid=21706672|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":16\" /> Influenza-like illnesses had been documented in Europe since at least [[Charlemagne]],<ref name=\":02\" /> with 1357's outbreak the first to be called ''influenza'',<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> but the 1510 flu pandemic is the first to be pathologically described<ref>{{Cite book|last=Riverside|first=Clifford E. Trafzer, University of California|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1QJN9xo3JUC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA109&dq=flu+of+1510&hl=en|title=Forgotten Voices: Death Records of the Yakama, 1888-1964|last2=McCoy|first2=Robert R.|date=2009-03-20|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8108-6648-5|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=109|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/11/101112141130.htm|title=Scientists explore 1510 influenza pandemic and lessons learned|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> following communication advances brought about by the [[printing press]]. Flu became more widely referred to as ''coqueluche'' and ''coccolucio'' in [[Kingdom of France|France]] and [[Kingdom of Sicily|Sicily]] during this epidemic,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N6FLAAAAYAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA332&dq=L'epidemie+de+1510+mezeray&hl=en|title=Dictionnaire encyclop\u00e9dique des sciences m\u00e9dicales|date=1877|publisher=Asselin|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=332|language=fr}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> variations of which became the most popular names for flu in [[early modern Europe]].<ref name=\":02\" /> The pandemic caused significant disruption in government, church, and society<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\"500th\" /> with near-universal infection<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=SCHWEICH|first=Heinrich|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z_hZAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=die+epidemie+die+jahres+1510&hl=en|title=Die Influenza. Ein historischer und \u00e4tiologischer Versuch ... Mit einer Vorrede von ... J. F. C. Hecker|last2=HECKER|first2=Justus Friedrich Carl|date=1836|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=57|language=de}}</ref> and a mortality rate of around 1%.<ref name=\":02\" /> \n\n== Asia ==\nThe 1510 flu is suspected of originating in East Asia,<ref name=\":02\" /> possibly [[China]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Gregor Horst asserts in ''Operum Medicorum tombs primus'' (1661) that the disease came from the Asia and spread along trade routes<ref name=\":02\" /> before attacking the Middle East and North Africa. German medical writer [[Justus Hecker]] suggested the 1510 influenza most likely came from Asia because of the historical nature of other influenza viruses to originate there in more recent pandemics.\n[[File:Eastern Mediterranean and Aegean Sea. Battista Agnese, PORTOLAN ATLAS (Italy ca. 1550).jpg|thumb|353x353px|Influenza had spread in North Africa before arriving in Europe.]]\n\n=== Middle East ===\nThe flu spread along trade routes towards North Africa,<ref name=\":02\" /> traveling southwest through the Middle East. Frequently visited cities like [[Jerusalem]] and [[Mecca]] would have almost certainly been reached by the flu, with large volumes of people destined to travel to [[Egypt]], North Africa, and the [[Ottoman Empire]].\n\n== Africa ==\nIt is generally understood that the 1510 influenza had spread in Africa before Europe.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> Influenza was likely across North Africa before crossing continents through the Mediterranean, arriving in [[Malta]]<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Stedman|first=Thomas Lathrop|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=DqEwAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&pg=GBS.PA11|title=Twentieth Century Practice: Infectious diseases|date=1898|publisher=W. Wood|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=11|language=en}}</ref> where British historian [[Thomas Vowler Short]] believes the \"island of ''Melite'' in ''Africa''\" became the 1510 flu's springboard into Europe.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /> <br />\n[[File:General map of Malta.svg|thumb|146x146px|The disease came to Malta on crews infected in Africa.|left]]\n== Europe ==\nEurope's internationally-traveled cities and flu's highly contagious nature enabled its spread through European populations. The 1510 flu disrupted royal courts, church services, and social life across Europe. Contemporary chroniclers and those who've read their accounts observed how entire populations were attacked at once,<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> which is how the disease first received the name ''influenza'' (from the belief that such outbreaks were caused by influences like stars or cold).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=A. Mir|first=Shakil|date=December 2009|title=History of Swine Flu|url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/774f5d6553eeae3107b5b114f055b64f/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=54966|journal=JK Science|publisher=PG Department of Pharmacology, Govt Medical College, Srinagar|volume=8|pages=163|via=ProQuest}}</ref> [[Turin]] professor Francisco Vallerioli (aka Valleriola) writes that the 1510 flu featured \"Constriction of breathing, and beginning with a hoarseness of voice and... shivering. Not long after that there being a cooked humor which fills the lungs.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Physicians like Valleriola described the 1510 flu as more fatal to children<ref>{{Cite book|last=Vaughan|first=Warren Taylor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lhc6AQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Influenza: An Epidemiologic Study|date=1921|publisher=American journal of hygiene|year=|isbn=|location=Baltimore, Maryland|pages=157|language=en}}</ref> and those who were bled.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />  Lawyer Francesco Muralto noted that \"the disease killed 10 people out of a thousand in one day,\" supporting a fatality rate of around 1%.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Sicily and the Italian Kingdoms ===\n[[File:Italy map 1584.jpg|thumb|Flu arrived in Sicily from [[Malta]], and quickly spread along the Italian coast.]]\nThe first cases of influenza began to appear in [[Sicily]] around July<ref name= Alibrandi>{{cite journal|last=Alibrandi|first=Rosamaria|title=When early modern Europe caught the flu. A scientific account of pandemic influenza in sixteenth century Sicily|journal=Medicina Historica|volume=2|pages=19-25}}</ref> after the arrival of infected merchant ships from [[Malta]].<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Parkin|first=John|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=9RcDAAAAQAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA35|title=Epidemiology; or, The remote cause of epidemic diseases in the animal and in the vegetable creation|date=1880|publisher=J. and A. Churchill|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xbo0AQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA220&dq=La+coqueluche+de+1510&hl=en|title=Dictionnaire encyclop\u00e9dique des sciences m\u00e9dicales: publi\u00e9 sous la direction de MM. les docteurs Raige-Delorme et A. Dechambre|date=1882|publisher=P. Asselin, S' de Lab\u00e9, V. Masson et fils|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=220|language=fr}}</ref> In Sicily it was commonly called ''coccolucio'' for the hoods the sick often wore over their heads.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Potter|first=C. W.|date=2001|title=A history of influenza|url=https://sfamjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1046/j.1365-2672.2001.01492.x|journal=Journal of Applied Microbiology|language=en|volume=91|issue=4|pages=572\u2013579|doi=10.1046/j.1365-2672.2001.01492.x|issn=1365-2672}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beveridge|first=W.I.B|date=1991|title=The Chronicle of Influenza Epidemics|url=|journal=History and Philosophy of the Life Sciences|volume=13|pages=223-234|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref name=\"catarrhal\">{{cite book|last=Thomson|first=Theophilus|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Annals_of_Influenza_Or_Epidemic_Catarrha/INc0AQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1|title=Annals of Influenza or Epidemic Catarrhal Fever in Great Britain|date=1852|publisher=The Sydenham Society Instituted|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=3-4|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Influenza quickly spread out along the Mediterranean coasts of Italy and southern France<ref name=Alibrandi/> via merchant ships leaving Sicilian harbors.  \n\nIn [[Emilia-Romagna]], Tommasino de' Bianchi recorded the recovery of [[Modena|Modena's]] first cases on 13 July 1510, writing that in the city \"there appears an illness that lasts three days with a great fever, and headache and then they rise .. but there remains a terrible cough that lasts maybe eight days, and then they recover.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Morens|first=David|last2=North|first2=Michael|last3=Taubenberger|first3=Jeffrey|date=4 December 2011|title=Eyewitness accounts of the 1510 influenza pandemic in Europe|url=https://www.thelancet.com/action/showPdf?pii=S0140-6736%2810%2962204-0|journal=Lancet|volume=367|pages=1894-1895|via=The Lancet}}</ref> This data would indicate that the first cases flu, which has an incubation period of one to four days, began to fall ill in the Emilia-Romagna region around late June or early July. In [[Bologna]] an 8 year-old named Ugo Bancopagni, who would later become [[Pope Gregory XIII]], became gravely ill with flu but recovered without permanent complications.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n[[Pope Julius II]] attributed the outbreaks in [[Rome]] and the [[Holy See]] to God's wrath.<ref name=\":02\" /> [[Pope Gregory XIII]] would later blame the 1510 influenza in France on the resistance of [[Louis XII of France|King Louis XII]] to divine authority.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n=== Central Europe ===\n[[File:Achilles Pirminius Gasser.JPG|thumb|Achilles Gasser mentions an epidemic of \"catarrhal fever\" in upper Germany.<ref name=\":9\" />|alt=|259x259px]]\nFlu spread over the Alps into Switzerland and the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. In Switzerland it is documented as being called ''das Gruppie'' by the [[Mellingen]] chronicler Anton Tegenfeld,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Karsten|first=Gustaf|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Journal_of_English_and_Germanic_Phil/VF-qD7s4txoC?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=1510+flu+england&pg=PA513&printsec=frontcover|title=The Journal of English and German Philology|publisher=University of Illinois, Urbana-Champagne|year=1920|isbn=|location=Urbana-Champagne|pages=513}}</ref> the flu nickname then preferred by German-speaking Europeans. A respiratory illness seemed to have menaced the Canton of Aargua in June, with the population falling ill with sniffling, coughing, and fatigue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Schindler|first=Wolfgang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3OetxIToFvIC&pg=PA344&lpg=PA344&dq=das+gruppie+1510+coqueluche&source=bl&ots=Pm2gpmJIuQ&sig=ACfU3U13GMtsaGUKj9hWLJ4UB3gO0CSjLA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjs-rq618LoAhUWpp4KHYQ4CFAQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=das%20gruppie%201510%20coqueluche&f=false|title=Grippe, Kamm und Eulenspiegel: Festschrift f\u00fcr Elmar Seebold zum 65. Geburtstag|last2=Untermann|first2=J\u00fcrgen|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=1999|isbn=978-3-11-015617-1|location=|pages=244|language=de}}</ref> German physician [[Achilles Gasser]] records a deadly epidemic spreading over the Holy Roman Empire's upper Kingdoms, branching into the cities and the \"whole mankind:\" ''Mira qua edam Epidemia mortales per urbes hanc totamque adeo superiorem Germaniam corripiebat, qua aegri IV vel V ad summum dies molestissimis destillationibus laborabant ac ration privati instar phrenicorum furebant, atque inde iterum convalescebant, paucissimis ad Gorcum demissis.''<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nAndr\u00e9 de Burgo's letters dated 24 August 1510 indicate [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Austria]] had to intervene at a royal assembly between her father, [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Maximilian I]], and [[Louis XII of France]] because the King of France was too sick with \"coqueluche\" to be spoken to.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Louis|first=X. I. I.|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=7b2c3BKPPVgC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA287|title=Lettres du roi Louis XII et du cardinal Georges d'Amboise: depuis 1504 \u00e0 1514|last2=Godefroy|date=1712|publisher=Foppens|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=287-288|language=fr}}</ref> Influenza spread out from the Holy Roman Empire towards Northern Europe, the [[Baltic states]],<ref name=\":11\" /> and west towards [[Kingdom of France|France]] and [[Kingdom of England|England]].<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:France XVe si\u00e8cl2e.jpg|thumb|It quickly spread to France's southern port cities first, then westward from the Alps to Paris.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />|left]]\nArriving aboard infected sailors from Sicily, influenza struck the [[Kingdom of France]] through the ports of [[Marseille]] and [[Nice]] and spread through the international crowds of the shipyards. It was referred to as ''cephalie catarrhal'' or more commonly ''coqueluche''.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Katona|first=Mihaly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CapNAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Abhandlung \u00fcber die Grippe (Influenza) in Wien in dem Jahre 1833|date=1833|publisher=Edl. v. Schmid|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=25-27|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Desruelles|first=Henry-Marie-Joseph|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Go9fAAAAcAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA22&dq=coqueluche+de+1510&hl=en|title=Traite De La Coqueluche, d'apres les Principes de la Doctrine Physiologique|publisher=J. B. Bailliere|year=1827|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=22|language=fr}}</ref> [[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray|M\u00e9zeray]] traces the etymology of ''coqueluche'' to the 1410s<ref name=\":5\" /> when sufferers would wear bonnets resembling coqueluchons, a kind of monk's cowl. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Doyen|first=Guillaume Le|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=wz5wdUawOpoC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PP1|title=Annalles et chronicques du pais de Laval et parties circonvoisines depuis l'an de Nostre Seigneur Ihesu-Crist 1480 jusq\u00fa \u00e0 l'ann\u00e9e 1537, avec un pr\u00e9ambule retrospectif du temps anticque jadis|date=1857|publisher=H. Godbert|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=134|language=fr}}</ref>French surgeon [[Ambroise Par\u00e9]] describes the outbreak as having been a \"rheumatic affliction of the head...with constriction of the heart and lungs.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Merchants, pilgrims, and other travelers from the south and east spread the virus throughout the western Mediterranean in July.<ref name=\":4\" /> By August it had appear in [[Tours]] and rapidly propagated itself throughout France, sickening the entire country by September.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Corradi|first=Alfonso|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EMFdvvQlL4AC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA20&dq=Influenza+de+1510+spain&hl=en|title=Annali delle epidemie occorse in Italia dalle prime memorie fino al 1850 scritti da Alfonso Corradi: Dal 1501 a tutto il 1600 con una tavola delle cose piu memorabili si della 1. che della 2. parte|date=1867|publisher=Tipi Gamberini e Parmeggiani|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=19|language=it}}</ref> French poet and historian Jean Bouchet, employed by King Louis XII's Royal Court, wrote that the epidemic \"appeared in the entire Kingdom of France, as much in the towns as in the countryside.\"<ref name=\":02\" />  \n\n''Coqueluche'' filled up the hospitals in France.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/La_Revue_mondiale/Ze3I8lnlJAQC?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=l%27epidemie+de+1510&dq=l%27epidemie+de+1510&printsec=frontcover|title=La Revue Mondial|publisher=Harvard University|year=1919|isbn=|location=Cambridge, MA|pages=262}}</ref> King Louis XII's National Assembly of [[Bishop|Bishops]], [[Prelate|Prelates]], and university [[Professor|professors]] scheduled for September 1510 was delayed because of the intensity of the flu in [[Paris]]. <ref name=\"500th\" /> [[Jean Fernel]] (aka Fernelius), physician to [[Henry III of France]], compares the 1557 influenza to the 1510 epidemic which attacked everyone with fever, a heaviness in their head, and profound coughing.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=DqEwAAAAIAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA11|title=Twentieth Century Practice: An International Encyclopedia of Modern Medical Science by Leading Authors of Europe and America|publisher=W. Wood|year=1898|isbn=|editor-last=Stedman|editor-first=Thomas|volume=15|location=New York|pages=11}}</ref> Up to 1000 Parisians per day were dying at the height of the \"1510 peste.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7yzFlQ-YzTsC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=1000+personnes+chaque+jour+peste+1510&hl=en|title=Quintessence de l'\u00e9conomie politique transcendante \u00e0 l'usage des \u00e9lecteurs et des philosophes par le baron de M\u00fcnster|date=1842|publisher=Dutertre|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=72|language=fr}}</ref> French historian [[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray|Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zery]] mentions that it disrupted judicial proceeding and colleges,<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> and that the 1510 flu was more widespread and deadly in France than in other countries.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bergeron|first=Georges|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i_--syugmU8C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=Des Caract\u00e8rs G\u00e9n\u00e9raux des Affections Catarrhals Aigues|date=1874|publisher=A. Delahaye|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=35|language=fr}}</ref>\n[[File:Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray.jpg|thumb|[[Fran\u00e7ois Eudes de M\u00e9zeray]] had access to original documents describing the influenza of 1510.<ref name=\":02\" />]]\n\n[[Georges d'Amboise|Cardinal Georges d'Amboise]], a close friend and advisor to the King of France, is sometimes believed to have died of influenza since his health sharply declined after arriving in Lyons in May 1510.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wright|first=Thomas|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=XstBAAAAcAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA612|title=The History of France: From the Earliest Period to the Present Time|date=1856|publisher=London Print. and Publishing Company|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=A.D. 1510|language=en}}</ref>  The cardinal, also known as Monseigneur le Ledat, made his final testimony and recited [[Sacraments of the Catholic Church|Sacraments]] around May 22<ref>{{Cite book|last=Louis|first=X. I. I.|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=7b2c3BKPPVgC&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA233|title=Lettres du roi Louis XII et du cardinal Georges d'Amboise: depuis 1504 \u00e0 1514|last2=Godefroy|date=1712|publisher=Foppens|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=233|language=fr}}</ref> before he died on the 25. His sudden decline in health and flu's arrival in Europe around early summer have created uncertainty as to whether he died of gout or influenza, but \"coqueluche\" is not mentioned in French royal correspondence that year until August.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== England and Ireland ===\nBritish medical historian [[Charles Creighton]] claims there is one foreign account of the 1510 flu in England,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|last=Creighton|first=Charles|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=CyoJAAAAIAAJ&hl=en&pg=GBS.PA399|title=A History of Epidemics in Britain ...|date=1891|publisher=The University Press|year=|isbn=|location=Cambridge, UK|pages=399-400|language=en}}</ref> but does not elaborate.<ref name=\":11\" /> An epidemiological study of past influenza pandemics reviewing previous medical historians has found England was affected in 1510.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x7SJoXpeUrAC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&hl=en|title=The American Journal of Hygiene: Monographic series|date=1921|publisher=Johns Hopkins Press|year=|isbn=|location=John Hopkins University|pages=7|language=en}}</ref> [[Jean Fernel|Fernel]] and [[Ambroise Par\u00e9|Par\u00e9]] suggest that the 1510 influenza \"spread to almost all countries of the world, except the New World.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> There were reports of symptoms like \"gastrodynia\" and noteworthy murrain among cattle.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kilbourne|first=E. D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybkpBgAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA6&dq=1510+influenza&hl=en|title=Influenza|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-1-4684-5239-6|location=New York|pages=6|language=en}}</ref> The 1510 flu is also recorded to have reached [[Ireland]].<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Spain and Portugal ===\n[[File:UBBasel Map 1500-1599 Kartenslg AA 131.tif|thumb|left|Influenza spread to [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]] around the same time it reached the Alps.|302x302px]]\nInfluenza reached the [[Iberian Peninsula]] early after Italy, due to the highly interconnected trade and pilgrimage routes between Spain, Portugal, and the Italian kingdoms. Cases began to appear in Portugal around the same time the disease entered the Holy Roman Empire.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /> Spanish cities were reportedly \"dispopulated\" by the 1510 flu.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|last=Ryan|first=Jeffrey R.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t13C_eWhOX4C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA16&dq=spanish+cities+were+dispopulated&hl=en|title=Pandemic Influenza: Emergency Planning and Community Preparedness|date=2008-08-01|publisher=CRC Press|year=|isbn=978-1-4200-6088-1|location=|pages=16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The Americas ==\n[[File:Hispaniola Vinckeboons4.jpg|thumb|Influenza previously attacked the [[Island of Santo Domingo]] in 1493 with severe consequences. |322x322px]]\nThere are no records of influenza affecting the [[New World]] in 1510,<ref name=\":02\" /> even though numerous other European powers like France, England, and Portugal were sending their first fleets of ships to the [[New World]] after [[Spain]]. Influenza had previously afflicted the Isle of Santo Domingo (now [[Hispaniola]]) in [[1493]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guerre, M.D.|first=Francisco|date=Fall 1988|title=The Earliest American Epidemic: The Influenza of 1493|url=|journal=Social Science History|volume=12|pages=305-325|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n\n== Medicine and Treatment ==\nBlistering on the back of the head and shoulders was one form of treatment prescribed in Europe for the flu.<ref name=\":02\" /> [[Ambroise Par\u00e9|Par\u00e9]] regarded the common treatments of [[bloodletting]] and [[purgation]] to be especially dangerous to 1510's flu patients.<ref name=\":02\" /> Supraorbital pain and vision problems were symptoms<ref name=\":13\" /> of ''coqueluche'', so sufferers may have felt tempted to wear hoods due to light sensitivity. [[Thomas Vowler Short|Short]] describes some medicinal treatments for the 1510 flu including \"Bole Armoniac, oily lintus, pectoral troches, and decoctions.\"<ref name=\"catarrhal\" />\n\n== Origin of 1510 Influenza ==\n[[Justus Friedrich Carl Hecker|Justus Hecker]] and John Parkin presume the 1510 influenza originated from East Asia because of the historical nature of other influenzas originating from said region,<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|last=Hecker|first=Justus Friedrich Carl|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xf5CAQAAIAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&q=1510&hl=en|title=The epidemics of the middle ages|last2=Babington|first2=Benjamin Guy|date=1859|publisher=Tr\u00fcbner & co.|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=202-205|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gordon|first=Sir Charles Alexander|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KC0AAAAAQAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA348&dq=history+of+epidemics+in+china+1510&hl=en|title=An Epitome of the Reports of the Medical Officers to the Chinese Imperial Maritime Customs Service, from 1871 to 1882: With Chapters on the History of Medicine in China, Materia Medica, Epidemics, Famine, Ethnology, and Chronology in Relation to Medicine and Public Health|date=1884|publisher=Bailli\u00e8re, Tindall, and Cox|year=|isbn=|location=London|pages=348|language=en}}</ref> while Gregor Horst documented that the 1510 flu spread along trade routes from East Asia to Africa before reaching Europe in 1661.<ref name=\":02\" /> Influenza viruses sometimes leap from Asia's migratory water fowl after massive migrations congregate near water sources for humans and domesticated animals (which can function as a cross-species catalysts for creating new strains of pandemic flu).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ma|first=Wenjun|last2=Kahn|first2=Robert E|last3=Richt|first3=Juergen A|date=2008-11-27|title=The pig as a mixing vessel for influenza viruses: Human and veterinary implications|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2702078/|journal=Journal of molecular and genetic medicine : an international journal of biomedical research|volume=3|issue=1|pages=158\u2013166|issn=1747-0862|pmc=2702078|pmid=19565018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/MPH-Modules/PH/PH709_Influenza/PH709_Influenza4.html|title=The Origin of New Flu Strains|website=sphweb.bumc.bu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> European chroniclers noticed that the 1510 influenza did appear in North Africa before Europe, which has lead some medical historians to suggest it may have developed there<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Bray|first=R. S.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRHbDwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA196&dq=1510+influenza+pandemic+asia&hl=en&source=newbks_fb#v=onepage&q=1510%20influenza%20pandemic%20asia&f=false|title=Armies of Pestilence: The Impact of Disease on History|date=|publisher=ISD LLC|year=1996|isbn=978-0-7188-4816-3|location=Cambridge, England|pages=196-197|language=en}}</ref>(parts of [[North Africa]] also lie along migratory bird ways, specifically the east Africa-West Asia and Black Sea-Mediterranean routes, that make it vulnerable to spontaneous reassortment of pandemic flu viruses).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baghi|first=Hossein Bannazadeh|last2=Soroush|first2=Mohammad Hossein|date=2018-05-01|title=Influenza: the role of the Middle East and north Africa?|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(18)30213-5/abstract|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases|language=English|volume=18|issue=5|pages=498|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(18)30213-5|issn=1473-3099|pmid=29695361}}</ref> But there remains no chronicled or biological evidence to suggest the 1510 flu originated from, as opposed to just spread in, Africa before reaching Europe.   \n\n== Debunking Suggestions of Whooping Cough ==\nThe 1510 ''coqueluche'' has been recognized as influenza by modern epidemiologists<ref name=\"500th\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> and medical historians.<ref name=\":11\" /> Suggestions that the 1510 ''coqueluche'' was [[whooping cough]] have been doubted<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lB5KAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA3&dq=whooping+cough+epidemics&hl=en|title=Whooping Cough: Essential Facts Concerning Whooping Cough, Its Prevention and Treatment with Appropriate Vaccines|date=1920|publisher=Eli Lilly & Company|year=|isbn=|location=Indianapolis, Indiana|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> because adult sufferers often experienced \"precipitous\"<ref name=\":02\" /> symptoms described by contemporaries like Thomasino de Bianchi<ref name=\":02\" /> or Valleriola as high fever for 3 days, headache, prostration, loss of sleep and appetite, delirium,<ref name=\":7\" /> a cough most severe on the 5th to 10th days, <ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P9dNAQAAMAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA542&dq=coqueluche+of+1510&hl=en|title=Encyclopedia of Practical Medicine: Variolla, Vaccination, Vericella, Cholera, Erysipelas, Whooping Cough, Hay Fever|date=1902|publisher=Saunders|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=542|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 21, 1918|editor-last=Stedman|editor-first=Thomas|title=Paris Epidemics of the XVI Century|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Medical_Record/Kt0yAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=coqueluche+of+1510+whooping+cough&pg=PA1076&printsec=frontcover|journal=Medical Record: A Weekly Journal of Medicine and Surgery|publisher=M.M. Wood & Co.|volume=94|pages=1076|via=}}</ref> lung congestion,<ref name=\":02\" /> and slow recovery beginning on the second week.<ref name=\"catarrhal\" /><ref name=\":14\" />Adults with pertussis will usually cough for weeks before becoming gradually more ill then recovering over a period of months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foundation.chestnet.org/patient-education-resources/pertussis/|title=Pertussis|website=CHEST Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IcQkAQAAIAAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PA120&dq=holland+whooping+cough+epidemic+1746&hl=en|title=American Association for the Study and Prevention of Infant Mortality: Transactions of the Annual Meeting - Milwaukee, October 19-21, 1916|publisher=Franklin Printing Company|year=1917|isbn=|location=Baltimore|pages=126|language=en}}</ref> The ''coqueluche'' of 1510 is considered to be influenza by most experts, from modern epidemiologists<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\"500th\" /> to medical historians<ref name=\":11\" /> due to its sudden onset of symptoms, explosive spread over Europe,<ref name=\":10\" /> and timelines of sickness to recovery. The first outbreak of whooping cough to be agreed on by most medical historians is [[Guillaume de Baillou|Guillaume de Baillou's]] description of an outbreak in Paris in [[1578]].<ref name=\":8\" />  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Influenza pandemics]]\n[[Category:Global health]]\n[[Category:Epidemics]]\n", "name_user": "DondeEstaElBurro?", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSicily and the Italian Kingdoms:changing it back, it was fine", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1510_Influenza_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Germiyanids", "text_new": "{{About||the place in Azerbaijan|Germiyan, Azerbaijan|Germiyan region in Iraqi Kurdistan|Beth Garmai}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Germiyan\n|common_name            = Germiyan\n|era                    = Late Medieval\n|government_type        = Monarchy\n|year_start = 1300\n|year_end  = 1429\n|p1     = Seljuq Sultanate of R\u00fbm\n|flag_p1   =\n|s1     = Ottoman Empire\n|flag_s1   = Flag of the Ottoman Empire.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_map  = Anatolia1300.png\n|image_map_caption = Beylik of Germiyan (light red) in 1300.\n|capital     = [[K\u00fctahya]]\n|common_languages =\n|religion     = Muslim\n|leader1   = [[Yakup I of Germiyan]]\n|leader2   = [[Yakup II of Germiyan]]\n|year_leader1 = 1300\u20131327\n|year_leader2 = 1402\u20131429\n|title_leader = Bey\n}}\n\nThe [[Anatolian beylik]] of '''Germiyan''' ({{lang-tr|Germiyano\u011fullar\u0131 Beyli\u011fi}} or ''Germiyan Beyli\u011fi'') with its capital in [[K\u00fctahya]] was one of the prominent frontier principalities established by the [[Kurds]]<ref>Carl F. Petry, 2008, ''The Cambridge History of Egypt'', p. 527, Northwestern University, Illinois, {{ISBN|9780521068857}}, Germianids: An Anatolian Turco-Kurdish dynasty</ref> and [[Turkish people|Turks]], after the decline of [[Seljuq Sultanate of R\u00fbm]].<ref>Peter Malcolm Holt, 1986, ''The Age of the Crusades: the Near East from the eleventh century to 1517'', p. 176, Longman,  University of Michigan, {{ISBN|0-582-49303-X}}, 9780582493032 The second of the eastern principalities, Germiyan, developed from a group, probably of mixed Kurdish and Turkish origin</ref><ref>Marios Philippides, ''Biblioteca apostolica vaticana - 1990, Byzantium, Europe, and the early Ottoman sultans, 1373-1513: an anonymous Greek chronicle of the seventeenth century'', p. 6, A.D. Caratzas, University of Michigan, {{ISBN|0-89241-430-8}}, {{ISBN|978-0-89241-430-7}}, Near Byzantine borders in Phrygia, the emirate of Germiyan was formed by a mixed population of Turks and Kurds, who had come from east of Malatya</ref> According to Agoston and Masters Germiyano\u011fullar\u0131 were [[Oghuz Turk|Turkomans]] who had immigrated to the west because of [[Mongol]] pressure in the second half of the 13th century.<ref>Gabor Agoston-Bruce Masters, ''Encyclopaedia of the Ottoman Empire'', p. 41 {{ISBN|978-0-8160-6259-1}}</ref> According to [[Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc]], the ruling clan belonged to [[Afshar (tribe)|Afshar]] branch of [[Oghuz Turks]].<ref name=koprulu>[[Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc]], (1937), ''The Origins of the Ottoman Empire'', p. 37</ref> Germiyanids likely came from [[Kerman]] or [[Fars Province]], perhaps headed west with [[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarazmshahs]]. After the death of [[Jalal ad-Din Mingburnu]], they remailed in [[Malatya]] area for a while, then moved to [[K\u00fctahya]], where they established the [[Anatolian beyliks|beylik]].<ref name=koprulu></ref>\n\nFor a brief period in the second half of the 14th century, Germiyan Dynasty was second only to [[Karamanid Dynasty]] in its rising power. But they were later taken over by the neighboring [[Osmano\u011flu family|Osmano\u011flu]] dynasty, who were to found the [[Ottoman Empire]] later.\n\nGermiyans played a crucial role in settling [[Turkish people|Turkish]] populations along the coastal regions of the [[Aegean Sea]], the founders of the Beyliks of [[Aydinids|Aydin]], [[Sarukhanids|Sarukhan]], [[\u0130nan\u00e7o\u011flu]] and [[Beylik of Mente\u015fe|Mente\u015fe]] having started out as Germiyan commanders.\n\nThey rebelled against the central power in 1283, upon the execution of the sultan [[Kaykhusraw III]] by the Mongols, and placing of [[Mesud II]] on the Seljuq throne. The struggle between combined Mongol-Seljuq forces based in [[Konya]] and the rebel forces of Germiyan continued until 1290. An agreement could only be reached in 1299, upon which the Germiyan Dynasty also entered into possession of [[Ankara]]. When the [[Ilkhanid]] governor [[Chupan|Emir \u00c7oban]] took over Anatolia in 1314, they declared allegiance and concentrated on raids towards the regions to their west.\n\nTheir western offshoots that were the Beyliks of [[Beylik of Mente\u015fe|Mente\u015fe]], [[Aydinids|Aydin]], [[Beylik of L\u00e2dik|Ladik]], [[Sarukhanids|Sarukhan]] and [[Karasids|Karasi]] were all subject to the Germiyan in the early periods of their foundation, while the Beyliks of [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] and [[Hamidids]] to the south had to rely on them for protection against attacks from the [[Karamanids]]. As for the northern regions of Anatolia, [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] sources record [[Umur Beg|Umur Bey]], a commander and son-in-law to the Germiyan family, to be the possessor of [[Paphlagonia]], where [[Jandarids|Jandarid]] dynasty was to rule only after Germiyan power weakened.\n\nTheir strong political entity was eventually surrounded by newer states established by their own former commanders, leaving the Germiyan no outlet to the coastline or to Byzantine territory. Their powerful Karamanid neighbors exerting constant pressure from the east, Germiyan gradually fell under the rising influence of the Ottomans.\n\nThe actual Turkish province of [[K\u00fctahya Province|K\u00fctahya]] was called the sub-province (''[[sanjak]]'') and later province (''[[vilayet]]'') of Germiyan until the early years of the [[Republic of Turkey]], when which it was renamed after its central town.\n\nThe founding dynasty of the beylik produced illustrious descendants either under the [[Ottoman Empire]] or in present-day Turkey, a notable one among these being the 19th century [[List of Ottoman Grand Viziers|grand vizier]] [[Abdurrahman Nureddin Pasha]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[S\u00fcleyman of Germiyan]]\n* [[Yakup II of Germiyan]]\n\n{{History of Turkey}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=D-WaKed2iNgC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA37&vq=germiyanid&dq=beylik&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&sig=vzENqPi4ZWXYa6Q4oP2NLXxXo9w (limited preview)] {{cite book | title = The Origins of the Ottoman Empire|ISBN=0-7914-0819-1 |author= Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc |author-link= Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc | translator=Gary Leiser |publisher=State University of New York Press| year= 1992}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{History of Turkey topics}}\n{{Seljuk Sultanate of Rum and Turkish Beyliks}}\n{{Medieval states in Anatolia}}\n\n[[Category:1429 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1300]]\n[[Category:Anatolian beyliks]]\n[[Category:History of K\u00fctahya]]\n[[Category:History of K\u00fctahya Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the place in Azerbaijan|Germiyan, Azerbaijan|Germiyan region in Iraqi Kurdistan|Beth Garmai}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = Germiyan\n|common_name            = Germiyan\n|era                    = Late Medieval\n|government_type        = Monarchy\n|year_start = 1300\n|year_end  = 1429\n|p1     = Seljuq Sultanate of R\u00fbm\n|flag_p1   =\n|s1     = Ottoman Empire\n|flag_s1   = Flag of the Ottoman Empire.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_map  = Anatolia1300.png\n|image_map_caption = Beylik of Germiyan (light red) in 1300.\n|capital     = [[K\u00fctahya]]\n|common_languages =\n|religion     = Muslim\n|leader1   = [[Yakup I of Germiyan]]\n|leader2   = [[Yakup II of Germiyan]]\n|year_leader1 = 1300\u20131327\n|year_leader2 = 1402\u20131429\n|title_leader = Bey\n}}\n\nThe [[Anatolian beylik]] of '''Germiyan''' ({{lang-tr|Germiyano\u011fullar\u0131 Beyli\u011fi}} or ''Germiyan Beyli\u011fi'') with its capital in [[K\u00fctahya]] was one of the prominent frontier principalities established by the [[Kurds]]<ref>Carl F. Petry, 2008, ''The Cambridge History of Egypt'', p. 527, Northwestern University, Illinois, {{ISBN|9780521068857}}, Germianids: An Anatolian Turco-Kurdish dynasty</ref> and [[Turkish people|Turks]], after the decline of [[Seljuq Sultanate of R\u00fbm]].<ref>Peter Malcolm Holt, 1986, ''The Age of the Crusades: the Near East from the eleventh century to 1517'', p. 176, Longman,  University of Michigan, {{ISBN|0-582-49303-X}}, 9780582493032 The second of the eastern principalities, Germiyan, developed from a group, probably of mixed Kurdish and Turkish origin</ref><ref>Marios Philippides, ''Biblioteca apostolica vaticana - 1990, Byzantium, Europe, and the early Ottoman sultans, 1373-1513: an anonymous Greek chronicle of the seventeenth century'', p. 6, A.D. Caratzas, University of Michigan, {{ISBN|0-89241-430-8}}, {{ISBN|978-0-89241-430-7}}, Near Byzantine borders in Phrygia, the emirate of Germiyan was formed by a mixed population of Turks and Kurds, who had come from east of Malatya</ref> According to Agoston and Masters Germiyano\u011fullar\u0131 were [[Oghuz Turk|Turkomans]] who had immigrated to the west because of [[Mongol]] pressure in the second half of the 13th century.<ref>Gabor Agoston-Bruce Masters, ''Encyclopaedia of the Ottoman Empire'', p. 41 {{ISBN|978-0-8160-6259-1}}</ref> According to [[Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc]], the ruling clan belonged to [[Afshar (tribe)|Afshar]] branch of [[Oghuz Turks]].<ref name=koprulu>[[Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc]], (1937), ''The Origins of the Ottoman Empire'', p. 37</ref> Germiyanids likely came from [[Kerman]] or [[Fars Province]], perhaps headed west with [[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarazmshahs]]. After the death of [[Jalal ad-Din Mingburnu]], they remailed in [[Malatya]] area for a while, then moved to [[K\u00fctahya]], where they established the [[beylik]].<ref name=koprulu></ref>\n\nFor a brief period in the second half of the 14th century, Germiyan Dynasty was second only to [[Karamanid Dynasty]] in its rising power. But they were later taken over by the neighboring [[Osmano\u011flu family|Osmano\u011flu]] dynasty, who were to found the [[Ottoman Empire]] later.\n\nGermiyans played a crucial role in settling [[Turkish people|Turkish]] populations along the coastal regions of the [[Aegean Sea]], the founders of the Beyliks of [[Aydinids|Aydin]], [[Sarukhanids|Sarukhan]], [[\u0130nan\u00e7o\u011flu]] and [[Beylik of Mente\u015fe|Mente\u015fe]] having started out as Germiyan commanders.\n\nThey rebelled against the central power in 1283, upon the execution of the sultan [[Kaykhusraw III]] by the Mongols, and placing of [[Mesud II]] on the Seljuq throne. The struggle between combined Mongol-Seljuq forces based in [[Konya]] and the rebel forces of Germiyan continued until 1290. An agreement could only be reached in 1299, upon which the Germiyan Dynasty also entered into possession of [[Ankara]]. When the [[Ilkhanid]] governor [[Chupan|Emir \u00c7oban]] took over Anatolia in 1314, they declared allegiance and concentrated on raids towards the regions to their west.\n\nTheir western offshoots that were the Beyliks of [[Beylik of Mente\u015fe|Mente\u015fe]], [[Aydinids|Aydin]], [[Beylik of L\u00e2dik|Ladik]], [[Sarukhanids|Sarukhan]] and [[Karasids|Karasi]] were all subject to the Germiyan in the early periods of their foundation, while the Beyliks of [[S\u00e2hib Ata]] and [[Hamidids]] to the south had to rely on them for protection against attacks from the [[Karamanids]]. As for the northern regions of Anatolia, [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] sources record [[Umur Beg|Umur Bey]], a commander and son-in-law to the Germiyan family, to be the possessor of [[Paphlagonia]], where [[Jandarids|Jandarid]] dynasty was to rule only after Germiyan power weakened.\n\nTheir strong political entity was eventually surrounded by newer states established by their own former commanders, leaving the Germiyan no outlet to the coastline or to Byzantine territory. Their powerful Karamanid neighbors exerting constant pressure from the east, Germiyan gradually fell under the rising influence of the Ottomans.\n\nThe actual Turkish province of [[K\u00fctahya Province|K\u00fctahya]] was called the sub-province (''[[sanjak]]'') and later province (''[[vilayet]]'') of Germiyan until the early years of the [[Republic of Turkey]], when which it was renamed after its central town.\n\nThe founding dynasty of the beylik produced illustrious descendants either under the [[Ottoman Empire]] or in present-day Turkey, a notable one among these being the 19th century [[List of Ottoman Grand Viziers|grand vizier]] [[Abdurrahman Nureddin Pasha]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[S\u00fcleyman of Germiyan]]\n* [[Yakup II of Germiyan]]\n\n{{History of Turkey}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=D-WaKed2iNgC&pg=PA36&lpg=PA37&vq=germiyanid&dq=beylik&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&sig=vzENqPi4ZWXYa6Q4oP2NLXxXo9w (limited preview)] {{cite book | title = The Origins of the Ottoman Empire|ISBN=0-7914-0819-1 |author= Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc |author-link= Mehmet Fuat K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc | translator=Gary Leiser |publisher=State University of New York Press| year= 1992}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{History of Turkey topics}}\n{{Seljuk Sultanate of Rum and Turkish Beyliks}}\n{{Medieval states in Anatolia}}\n\n[[Category:1429 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1300]]\n[[Category:Anatolian beyliks]]\n[[Category:History of K\u00fctahya]]\n[[Category:History of K\u00fctahya Province]]\n", "name_user": "Beshogur", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:beylik\u2192Anatolian beyliks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germiyanids"}
{"title_page": "Randall Woodfin", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Randall Woodfin\n|image       = Randall Woodfin - 2019.jpg\n|office      = 34th [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]\n|term_start  = November 28, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[William A. Bell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|5|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education   = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|randallwoodfin.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Randall Woodfin''' (born May 29, 1981) is an American lawyer and politician who is the 34th and current [[Mayor of Birmingham, Alabama|mayor of]] [[Birmingham, Alabama]], after winning the October 3, 2017, runoff against incumbent [[William A. Bell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/10/randall_woodfin_wins_birmingha.html|title=Randall Woodfin wins Birmingham mayor's race: What they're saying nationally|work=AL.com|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> He previously served as the President of the Birmingham City School Board (2013\u20132015) and as an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham since 2009.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nWoodfin was born and raised in Birmingham's North Birmingham and Crestwood neighborhoods. He attended North Birmingham Elementary School, Putnam Middle School, and [[Shades Valley High School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin attended [[Morehouse College]], where he majored in political science and served as president of Student Government Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/world/this-morehouse-alum-just-became-the-youngest-mayor-birmingham-modern-history/s0co6Rwv6D2KRIOpLUdPLK/|title=This Morehouse alum just became the youngest mayor of Birmingham in modern history|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Najja Parker|website=ajc}}</ref> Woodfin went on to earn his law degree from the [[Cumberland School of Law]] at [[Samford University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-Mayorship==\n[[File:Randall-Woodfin-profile-in-bet-size-768x512.jpg|thumb|right|Woodfin in October 2017.]]\n\nBetween college and law school, Woodfin worked for the Birmingham City Council, the Mayor's Office Division of Youth Services, and the Jefferson County Committee on Economic Opportunity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin unsuccessfully ran for the Birmingham Board of Education's District 3 seat in 2009, placing third in a four-person race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/birmingham-elections/2009/08/birmingham_board_of_education_1.html|title=Birmingham Board of Education: 4 new faces vie for District 3|date=2009-08-18|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, Woodfin became an assistant city attorney for the City of Birmingham, a position he held until being elected mayor in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Woodfin again ran for a seat on the school board, this time successfully.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/spotnews/2013/08/election_results_see_who_won_m.html|title=Birmingham election results: See who won mayor, City Council and school board elections|last=staff|first=AL com|date=2013-08-28|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> He was appointed president of the board two months after being elected<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2015/11/new_birmingham_board_of_educat.html|title=New leadership for Birmingham board of education|date=2015-11-20|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>; he held that position until 2015 and remained on the board until 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2015/11/new_birmingham_board_of_educat.html|title=New leadership for Birmingham board of education|date=2015-11-20|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin has also served as a board member of other community organizations, including the Alabama Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy, [[Birmingham Botanical Gardens (United States)|Birmingham Botanical Gardens]], and the Hispanic Interest Coalition of Alabama. He is a former board member of Birmingham Change Fund, American Red Cross, Birmingham Education Foundation, Birmingham Cultural Alliance, S.T.A.I.R., and past President of the Birmingham chapter of the Morehouse College Alumni Association. Woodfin is a graduate of Leadership Birmingham class of 2014, Leadership Alabama class of 2016, and served as a featured speaker at [[TEDx]] Birmingham 2017.\n\nWoodfin served as the Alabama state director for [[Hillary Clinton]]'s 2016 presidential campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/04/politics/randall-woodfin-birmingham-bernie-sanders/index.html|title=A Sanders-backed candidate was elected mayor in the south|last=Editor-at-large|first=Analysis by Chris Cillizza, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==2017 Mayoral Campaign==\nWoodfin announced his run for Birmingham mayor in August 2016, challenging incumbent candidate William Bell along with 10 other candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2016/08/22/assistant-city-attorney-to-run-for-mayor.html|title=Assistant city attorney to run for mayor|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In the [[2017 Birmingham, Alabama mayoral election|general election]], held on August 22, 2017, Woodfin won 40% of the vote, triggering a runoff election with Bell, who placed second. Woodfin won the October 3 runoff with 58.95% of the vote, becoming the city's youngest mayor in over 120 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, Woodfin criticized Bell's failure to improve Birmingham residents' quality of life<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wbhm.org/feature/2017/tuesday-runoff-election-pits-bell-vs-woodfin/|title=In Tuesday's Mayoral Runoff, Bell Touts Experience, Woodfin Pushes Change|website=WBHM 90.3|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and promised to focus his administration on revitalization of the city's 99 neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/people_want_change.html|title=Randall Woodfin defeats William Bell in mayor's race|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBell criticized Woodfin for receiving out-of-state contributions during the campaign; Woodfin argued that it was the only way to combat the incumbent candidate's sizable local donor base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-bells-fundraising-allegations-false-misleading/|title=Woodfin: Bell\u2019s Fundraising Allegations Are \u2018False and Misleading\u2019|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-09-12|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin received support from Vermont Senator [[Bernie Sanders]], who recorded a robo-call telling voters that Woodfin would fight for Medicare for All. [[Our Revolution]] President [[Nina Turner]] visited Birmingham twice to campaign for Woodfin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/randall_woodfin_benefited_from.html|title=Randall Woodfin benefited from Bernie Sanders backing|last=Post|first=The Washington|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin has politically been compared to [[Jackson, Mississippi]] Mayor [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba|Chokwe Lumumba]], another [[Our Revolution]]-backed candidate elected in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/10/03/populists-are-on-the-march-in-the-south-bernie-backed-insurgent-randall-woodfin-defeats-birminghams-incumbent-mayor/|title=Populists Are on the March in the South: Bernie-Backed Insurgent Randall Woodfin Defeats Birmingham\u2019s Incumbent Mayor|last=Jilani|first=Zaid|date=2017-10-04|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mississippitoday.org/2018/10/09/mayors-lumumba-of-jackson-woodfin-of-birmingham-dish-on-poverty-solutions/|title=Mayors Lumumba of Jackson, Woodfin of Birmingham dish on poverty solutions|last=Nave|first=R. L.|last2=October 9|first2=Mississippi Today|date=2018-10-09|website=Mississippi Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13|last3=2018}}</ref>\n\n==Mayorship==\n[[Image:Randall Woodfin.jpg|thumb|left|Woodfin speaks at a town hall meeting in January 2019.]] \n\nIn March 2018, Woodfin's transition committee announced it had discovered that the city's pension fund had been consistently underfunded for more than 15 years, endangering the city's credit rating and retirement benefits for thousands of city employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/hole-balance-sheet-birminghams-impending-pension-crisis/|title=A Hole in the Balance Sheet: Birmingham\u2019s Impending Pension Crisis|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-04-16|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin increased funding to the pension fund by $2.9 million in the city's 2019 budget, and by $5.2 million in the city's 2020 budget \u2014 which Woodfin's administration claimed fully met the city's obligation to the fund for the first time in more than a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-highlights-moral-obligations-proposed-2020-budget/|title=Woodfin Highlights \u201cMoral Obligations\u201d of Proposed 2020 Budget|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2019-05-14|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin's administration has drawn criticism for a perceived lack of transparency, with [[AL.com]] columnist Kyle Whitmire calling Woodfin's attempts to block public information requests \"stalling and stonewalling\" and a violation of his campaign promises to increase transparency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/09/whats-randall-woodfin-hiding.html|title=Whitmire: What's Randall Woodfin hiding?|date=2019-09-06|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin endorsed [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 Democratic presidential primary]], despite having received [[Bernie Sanders]]' endorsement during his 2017 mayoral race. Woodfin cited Biden's ability to \"make sure down-ballot candidates can win\" as a primary reason for his endorsement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/12/birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-sen-joe-biden-in-2020-presidential-race.html|title=Woodfin makes endorsement in 2020 Democratic presidential race|date=2019-12-16|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theroot.com/exclusive-birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-jo-1840451074|title=Exclusive: Birmingham Mayor Randall Woodfin Endorses Joe Biden for President|website=The Root|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Neighborhood Revitalization=== \nIn his first two years in office, Woodfin budgeted $13 million for street resurfacing, $2.5 million toward clearing overgrown lots, and $6.5 million toward demolishing dilapidated structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/11/randall-woodfins-first-two-years.html|title=How Woodfin grades himself at 2 years|date=2019-11-24|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Woodfin has argued that his predecessor's policy regarding [[urban blight]] was \"not as aggressive as it needed to be\" and that it would be a \"priority\" for his administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/first-demolition-woodfin-promises-aggressive-approach-blight/|title=With First Demolition, Woodfin Promises \"Aggressive\" Approach to Blight|date=2017-12-01|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nBirmingham's high violent crime rate was a central plank of Woodfin's campaign platform; his nephew, Ralph Woodfin III, was shot and killed in August 2017, just weeks before the general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/08/tarrant_police_investigate_hom.html|title=Teen killed in Tarrant shooting was Birmingham mayoral candidate's nephew|work=AL.com|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Woodfin took office in November 2017, Birmingham Police Department Chief A.C. Roper announced his resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/police-chief-c-roper-retires-mayor-woodfin-looks-make-personnel-changes-city-hall/|title=Police Chief A.C. Roper Retires as Mayor Woodfin Looks to Make Personnel Changes at City Hall|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-11-29|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After a lengthy search, Woodfin appointed former [[Los Angeles Police Department]] commander Patrick D. Smith to the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-hires-la-commander-new-police-chief/|title=Birmingham Hires LA Commander to be New Police Chief|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-06-04|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Woodfin's administration unveiled a public service announcement campaign titled \"PEACE\" featuring 30-second videos of mothers of gun violence victims telling their stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2019/02/28/mayor-woodfin-unveils-peace-campaign-to-counteract-violent-crime/|title=Mayor Woodfin unveils PEACE Campaign to counteract violent crime|date=2019-02-28|website=The Official Website for the City of Birmingham, Alabama|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe city's homicide rate has stayed approximately the same since Woodfin took office; the city logged 117 homicides in 2017, 110 in 2018, and 112 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhamwiki.com/w/Birmingham_homicides_by_year#2010s|title=Birmingham homicides by year - Bhamwiki|website=www.bhamwiki.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin has maintained that total violent crime has dropped in the city during his tenure, and points to the police department's removal of thousands of guns from the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/07/birmingham-mayor-woodfin-gives-state-city-address/|title=Birmingham Mayor Woodfin gives State of the City address|last=Groover|first=Shilo|website=WBRC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nSeveral high-profile gun deaths \u2014 high-schooler Courtlin Arrington, 4-year-old Jurnee Coleman, Kamille \"Cupcake\" McKinney, and Sgt. Wytasha Carter \u2014 happened during Woodfin's first two years in office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/11/randall-woodfins-first-two-years.html|title=How Woodfin grades himself at 2 years|date=2019-11-24|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19===\nAlong with the Birmingham City Council, Woodfin's administration passed a $15 million [[COVID-19]] response plan in March 2020, allocating extra money for first responders' personal protective equipment, allocating overtime pay, and placing $1 million in a small business emergency loan fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2020/03/17/mayor-woodfins-15-million-covid-19-response-plan-approved-by-the-birmingham-city-council/|title=Mayor Woodfin's $15 million COVID-19 Response Plan Approved by the Birmingham City Council|website=www.birminghamal.gov|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin also urged the council to pass a \"shelter-in-place\" ordinance on March 24, which has been extended through the end of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-residents-ordered-shelter-place-leave-home-essential-activities/|title=Birmingham Residents Ordered to Shelter in Place, Leave Home for Only the Most Essential Activities|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2020-03-24|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Political Views==\nWoodfin identifies as a political [[centrism|moderate]]. In a 2019 interview with ''[[The Root]]'', Woodfin argued that \"being a moderate does not equal status quo... I support a lot of things on the left but\u2014if I\u2019m being real\u2014I also believe you gotta win.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theroot.com/exclusive-birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-jo-1840451074|title=Exclusive: Birmingham Mayor Randall Woodfin Endorses Joe Biden for President|website=The Root|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nWoodfin grew up with three siblings; his older brother Ralph was killed by gun violence in 2011. Woodfin's nephew Ralph Woodfin III was killed in August 2017. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin is single and identifies as [[Christian]]. He attends Sixth Avenue Baptist Church in Birmingham. He is a fan of [[Mannie Fresh]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[The Neptunes]], and [[Big K.R.I.T.]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons inline}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Randall Woodfin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William A. Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Alabama cities and mayors of 100,000 population |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodfin, Randall}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American mayors]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Alabama politics]]\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alabama lawyers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Randall Woodfin\n|image       = Randall Woodfin - 2019.jpg\n|office      = 34th [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]\n|term_start  = November 28, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[William A. Bell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|5|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education   = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|randallwoodfin.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Randall Woodfin''' (born May 29, 1981) is an American lawyer and politician who is the 34th and current [[Mayor of Birmingham, Alabama|mayor of]] [[Birmingham, Alabama]], after winning the October 3, 2017, runoff against incumbent [[William A. Bell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/10/randall_woodfin_wins_birmingha.html|title=Randall Woodfin wins Birmingham mayor's race: What they're saying nationally|work=AL.com|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> He previously served as the President of the Birmingham City School Board (2013\u20132015) and as an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham since 2009.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nWoodfin was born and raised in Birmingham's North Birmingham and Crestwood neighborhoods. He attended North Birmingham Elementary School, Putnam Middle School, and [[Shades Valley High School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin attended [[Morehouse College]], where he majored in political science and served as president of Student Government Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/world/this-morehouse-alum-just-became-the-youngest-mayor-birmingham-modern-history/s0co6Rwv6D2KRIOpLUdPLK/|title=This Morehouse alum just became the youngest mayor of Birmingham in modern history|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Najja Parker|website=ajc}}</ref> Woodfin went on to earn his law degree from the [[Cumberland School of Law]] at [[Samford University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-Mayorship==\n[[File:Randall-Woodfin-profile-in-bet-size-768x512.jpg|thumb|right|Woodfin in October 2017.]]\n\nBetween college and law school, Woodfin worked for the Birmingham City Council, the Mayor's Office Division of Youth Services, and the Jefferson County Committee on Economic Opportunity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin unsuccessfully ran for the Birmingham Board of Education's District 3 seat in 2009, placing third in a four-person race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/birmingham-elections/2009/08/birmingham_board_of_education_1.html|title=Birmingham Board of Education: 4 new faces vie for District 3|date=2009-08-18|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, Woodfin became an assistant city attorney for the City of Birmingham, a position he held until being elected mayor in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.randallwoodfin.com/about|title=ABOUT RANDALL|website=randallwoodfin|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Woodfin again ran for a seat on the school board, this time successfully.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/spotnews/2013/08/election_results_see_who_won_m.html|title=Birmingham election results: See who won mayor, City Council and school board elections|last=staff|first=AL com|date=2013-08-28|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> He was appointed president of the board two months after being elected<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2015/11/new_birmingham_board_of_educat.html|title=New leadership for Birmingham board of education|date=2015-11-20|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>; he held that position until 2015 and remained on the board until 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2015/11/new_birmingham_board_of_educat.html|title=New leadership for Birmingham board of education|date=2015-11-20|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin has also served as a board member of other community organizations, including the Alabama Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy, [[Birmingham Botanical Gardens (United States)|Birmingham Botanical Gardens]], and the Hispanic Interest Coalition of Alabama. He is a former board member of Birmingham Change Fund, American Red Cross, Birmingham Education Foundation, Birmingham Cultural Alliance, S.T.A.I.R., and past President of the Birmingham chapter of the Morehouse College Alumni Association. Woodfin is a graduate of Leadership Birmingham class of 2014, Leadership Alabama class of 2016, and served as a featured speaker at [[TEDx]] Birmingham 2017.\n\nWoodfin served as the Alabama state director for [[Hillary Clinton]]'s 2016 presidential campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/04/politics/randall-woodfin-birmingham-bernie-sanders/index.html|title=A Sanders-backed candidate was elected mayor in the south|last=Editor-at-large|first=Analysis by Chris Cillizza, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==2017 Mayoral Campaign==\nWoodfin announced his run for Birmingham mayor in August 2016, challenging incumbent candidate William Bell along with 10 other candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2016/08/22/assistant-city-attorney-to-run-for-mayor.html|title=Assistant city attorney to run for mayor|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In the [[2017 Birmingham, Alabama mayoral election|general election]], held on August 22, 2017, Woodfin won 40% of the vote, triggering a runoff election with Bell, who placed second. Woodfin won the October 3 runoff with 58.95% of the vote, becoming the city's youngest mayor in over 120 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, Woodfin criticized Bell's failure to improve Birmingham residents' quality of life<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wbhm.org/feature/2017/tuesday-runoff-election-pits-bell-vs-woodfin/|title=In Tuesday's Mayoral Runoff, Bell Touts Experience, Woodfin Pushes Change|website=WBHM 90.3|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and promised to focus his administration on revitalization of the city's 99 neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/people_want_change.html|title=Randall Woodfin defeats William Bell in mayor's race|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBell criticized Woodfin for receiving out-of-state contributions during the campaign; Woodfin argued that it was the only way to combat the incumbent candidate's sizable local donor base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-bells-fundraising-allegations-false-misleading/|title=Woodfin: Bell\u2019s Fundraising Allegations Are \u2018False and Misleading\u2019|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-09-12|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin received support from Vermont Senator [[Bernie Sanders]], who recorded a robo-call telling voters that Woodfin would fight for Medicare for All. [[Our Revolution]] President [[Nina Turner]] visited Birmingham twice to campaign for Woodfin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/randall_woodfin_benefited_from.html|title=Randall Woodfin benefited from Bernie Sanders backing|last=Post|first=The Washington|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin has politically been compared to [[Jackson, Mississippi]] Mayor [[Chokwe Antar Lumumba|Chokwe Lumumba]], another [[Our Revolution]]-backed candidate elected in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/10/03/populists-are-on-the-march-in-the-south-bernie-backed-insurgent-randall-woodfin-defeats-birminghams-incumbent-mayor/|title=Populists Are on the March in the South: Bernie-Backed Insurgent Randall Woodfin Defeats Birmingham\u2019s Incumbent Mayor|last=Jilani|first=Zaid|date=2017-10-04|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Mayorship==\n[[Image:Randall Woodfin.jpg|thumb|left|Woodfin speaks at a town hall meeting in January 2019.]] \n\nIn March 2018, Woodfin's transition committee announced it had discovered that the city's pension fund had been consistently underfunded for more than 15 years, endangering the city's credit rating and retirement benefits for thousands of city employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/hole-balance-sheet-birminghams-impending-pension-crisis/|title=A Hole in the Balance Sheet: Birmingham\u2019s Impending Pension Crisis|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-04-16|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin increased funding to the pension fund by $2.9 million in the city's 2019 budget, and by $5.2 million in the city's 2020 budget \u2014 which Woodfin's administration claimed fully met the city's obligation to the fund for the first time in more than a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-highlights-moral-obligations-proposed-2020-budget/|title=Woodfin Highlights \u201cMoral Obligations\u201d of Proposed 2020 Budget|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2019-05-14|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin's administration has drawn criticism for a perceived lack of transparency, with [[AL.com]] columnist Kyle Whitmire calling Woodfin's attempts to block public information requests \"stalling and stonewalling\" and a violation of his campaign promises to increase transparency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/09/whats-randall-woodfin-hiding.html|title=Whitmire: What's Randall Woodfin hiding?|date=2019-09-06|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin endorsed [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 Democratic presidential primary]], despite having received [[Bernie Sanders]]' endorsement during his 2017 mayoral race. Woodfin cited Biden's ability to \"make sure down-ballot candidates can win\" as a primary reason for his endorsement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/12/birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-sen-joe-biden-in-2020-presidential-race.html|title=Woodfin makes endorsement in 2020 Democratic presidential race|date=2019-12-16|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theroot.com/exclusive-birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-jo-1840451074|title=Exclusive: Birmingham Mayor Randall Woodfin Endorses Joe Biden for President|website=The Root|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Neighborhood Revitalization=== \nIn his first two years in office, Woodfin budgeted $13 million for street resurfacing, $2.5 million toward clearing overgrown lots, and $6.5 million toward demolishing dilapidated structures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/11/randall-woodfins-first-two-years.html|title=How Woodfin grades himself at 2 years|date=2019-11-24|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Woodfin has argued that his predecessor's policy regarding [[urban blight]] was \"not as aggressive as it needed to be\" and that it would be a \"priority\" for his administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/first-demolition-woodfin-promises-aggressive-approach-blight/|title=With First Demolition, Woodfin Promises \"Aggressive\" Approach to Blight|date=2017-12-01|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nBirmingham's high violent crime rate was a central plank of Woodfin's campaign platform; his nephew, Ralph Woodfin III, was shot and killed in August 2017, just weeks before the general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/08/tarrant_police_investigate_hom.html|title=Teen killed in Tarrant shooting was Birmingham mayoral candidate's nephew|work=AL.com|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Woodfin took office in November 2017, Birmingham Police Department Chief A.C. Roper announced his resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/police-chief-c-roper-retires-mayor-woodfin-looks-make-personnel-changes-city-hall/|title=Police Chief A.C. Roper Retires as Mayor Woodfin Looks to Make Personnel Changes at City Hall|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-11-29|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After a lengthy search, Woodfin appointed former [[Los Angeles Police Department]] commander Patrick D. Smith to the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-hires-la-commander-new-police-chief/|title=Birmingham Hires LA Commander to be New Police Chief|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-06-04|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Woodfin's administration unveiled a public service announcement campaign titled \"PEACE\" featuring 30-second videos of mothers of gun violence victims telling their stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2019/02/28/mayor-woodfin-unveils-peace-campaign-to-counteract-violent-crime/|title=Mayor Woodfin unveils PEACE Campaign to counteract violent crime|date=2019-02-28|website=The Official Website for the City of Birmingham, Alabama|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe city's homicide rate has stayed approximately the same since Woodfin took office; the city logged 117 homicides in 2017, 110 in 2018, and 112 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhamwiki.com/w/Birmingham_homicides_by_year#2010s|title=Birmingham homicides by year - Bhamwiki|website=www.bhamwiki.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin has maintained that total violent crime has dropped in the city during his tenure, and points to the police department's removal of thousands of guns from the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/07/birmingham-mayor-woodfin-gives-state-city-address/|title=Birmingham Mayor Woodfin gives State of the City address|last=Groover|first=Shilo|website=WBRC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nSeveral high-profile gun deaths \u2014 high-schooler Courtlin Arrington, 4-year-old Jurnee Coleman, Kamille \"Cupcake\" McKinney, and Sgt. Wytasha Carter \u2014 happened during Woodfin's first two years in office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/11/randall-woodfins-first-two-years.html|title=How Woodfin grades himself at 2 years|date=2019-11-24|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19===\nAlong with the Birmingham City Council, Woodfin's administration passed a $15 million [[COVID-19]] response plan in March 2020, allocating extra money for first responders' personal protective equipment, allocating overtime pay, and placing $1 million in a small business emergency loan fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2020/03/17/mayor-woodfins-15-million-covid-19-response-plan-approved-by-the-birmingham-city-council/|title=Mayor Woodfin's $15 million COVID-19 Response Plan Approved by the Birmingham City Council|website=www.birminghamal.gov|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin also urged the council to pass a \"shelter-in-place\" ordinance on March 24, which has been extended through the end of April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-residents-ordered-shelter-place-leave-home-essential-activities/|title=Birmingham Residents Ordered to Shelter in Place, Leave Home for Only the Most Essential Activities|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2020-03-24|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Political Views==\nWoodfin identifies as a political [[centrism|moderate]]. In a 2019 interview with ''[[The Root]]'', Woodfin argued that \"being a moderate does not equal status quo... I support a lot of things on the left but\u2014if I\u2019m being real\u2014I also believe you gotta win.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theroot.com/exclusive-birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-jo-1840451074|title=Exclusive: Birmingham Mayor Randall Woodfin Endorses Joe Biden for President|website=The Root|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nWoodfin grew up with three siblings; his older brother Ralph was killed by gun violence in 2011. Woodfin's nephew Ralph Woodfin III was killed in August 2017. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin is single and identifies as [[Christian]]. He attends Sixth Avenue Baptist Church in Birmingham. He is a fan of [[Mannie Fresh]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[The Neptunes]], and [[Big K.R.I.T.]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/bhammag/2018/07/everything_you_need_to_know_ab_1.html|title=Get to know Birmingham's millennial mayor|last=magazine|first=Birmingham|date=2018-07-09|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons inline}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Randall Woodfin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William A. Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Alabama cities and mayors of 100,000 population |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodfin, Randall}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American mayors]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Alabama politics]]\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alabama lawyers]]\n", "name_user": "Depressed Marvin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2017 Mayoral Campaign", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randall_Woodfin"}
{"title_page": "Amos Russel Wells", "text_new": "'''Amos Russel Wells''' (23 December 1862, in [[Glens Falls, New York]] \u2013 6 March 1933, in [[Massachusetts]]) was a [[United States]] [[editor]], [[author]] and [[professor]].\n\nHe graduated from [[Antioch College]] in 1883. He was professor of [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[geology]] at Antioch College from 1883 to 1891 and from 1891 editor of the ''Christian Endeavor World'', [[Boston]]. From 1901, he was associate author of ''Peloubet's Notes on the Sunday School Lessons''. He was a member of the International Sunday-School Lesson Committee. He was a voluminous author, no less than 63 titles being credited to his pen. His works include books dealing with young people's work, the Sunday school, juvenile fiction, poetry and devotional literature.\n\n==Notes==\n{{No footnotes|date=July 2013}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Wells, Amos Russel |year=1920}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.hymntime.com/tch/bio/w/e/l/wells_ar.htm |title=Amos Russel Wells |author=Hymntime.com |accessdate=23 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712233557/http://www.hymntime.com/tch/bio/w/e/l/wells_ar.htm |archivedate=12 July 2011 }}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, Amos Russel}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1933 deaths]]\n[[Category:Antioch College alumni]]\n[[Category:Antioch College faculty]]\n[[Category:American editors]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n\n\n{{christianity-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Amos Russel Wells''' (23 December 1862, in [[Glens Falls, New York]] \u2013 6 March 1933, in [[Massachusetts]]) was a [[United States]] [[editor]], [[author]] and [[professor]].\n\nHe graduated from [[Antioch College]] in 1883. He was professor of [[Greek language|Greek]] and [[geology]] at Antioch College from 1883 to 1891 and from 1891 editor of the ''Christian Endeavor World'', [[Boston]]. From 1901, he was associate author of ''Peloubet's Notes on the Sunday School Lessons''. He was a member of the International Sunday-School Lesson Committee. He was a voluminous author, no less than 63 titles being credited to his pen. His works include books dealing with young people's work, the Sunday school, juvenile fiction, poetry and devotional literature.\n\n==Notes==\n{{No footnotes|date=July 2013}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Wells, Amos Russel |year=1920}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://www.hymntime.com/tch/bio/w/e/l/wells_ar.htm |title=Amos Russel Wells |author=Hymntime.com |accessdate=23 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712233557/http://www.hymntime.com/tch/bio/w/e/l/wells_ar.htm |archivedate=12 July 2011 }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, Amos Russel}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1933 deaths]]\n[[Category:Antioch College alumni]]\n[[Category:Antioch College faculty]]\n[[Category:American editors]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n\n{{christianity-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amos_Russel_Wells"}
{"title_page": "EA Sports", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = EA Sports (Porco Dio viva il momentum e lo script. Siete da querelare.)\n| former_names = Electronic Arts Sports Network (1991\u20131993)\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1991}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people = Daryl Holt ([[Chief operating officer|COO]] and [[Vice-president|VP]])\n| num_employees =\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[Electronic Arts]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.easports.com/|easports.com}}\n}}\n\n\"Ea Sports \u00e8 una truffa, raga non comprate che il loro prodotto vi fa collassare il sistema cerebrale e nervoso\"'''EA Sports''' is a division of [[Electronic Arts]] that develops and publishes [[Sports game|sports video games]].  Formerly a marketing gimmick of Electronic Arts, in which they tried to imitate real-life sports networks by calling themselves the \"EA Sports Network\" (EASN) with pictures or endorsements with real commentators such as [[John Madden]], it soon grew up to become a sub-label on its own, releasing game series such as ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]'', ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]'', ''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'' and ''[[Madden NFL]]''.\n\nMost games under this brand are the merda are developed by [[EA Vancouver]], the studio of Electronic Arts in [[Burnaby]], [[British Columbia]] as well as [[EA Tiburon]] in [[Maitland, Florida]]. The main rival to EA Sports is [[2K Sports]]. Notably, both companies compete over the realm of NBA games. [[Konami]] is its rival in association football games.\n\nUnlike some other sports game companies, EA Sports has no special ties to a single platform, which means that all games are released for the bestselling active platforms, sometimes long after most of the other companies abandon them. For example, ''[[FIFA: Road to World Cup 98|FIFA 98]]'', ''[[Madden NFL 98]]'', ''[[NBA Live 98]]'', and ''[[NHL 98]]'' were released for the [[Sega Genesis]] and the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] throughout 1997; ''[[Madden NFL 2005]]'' and ''[[FIFA Football 2005|FIFA 2005]]'' had [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] releases in 2004 (''FIFA 2005'' and ''Madden NFL 2005'' were also the last two PlayStation titles to be released); and ''[[NCAA Football 08]]'' had an [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] release in 2007. ''[[Madden NFL 08]]'' also had [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] and Nintendo [[GameCube]] releases in 2007, and was the final title released for the GameCube, with ''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' following as the final Xbox title. Additionally, ''[[NASCAR Thunder 2003]]'' and ''[[NASCAR Thunder 2004]]'' were released not only for the [[PlayStation 2]], but for the original [[PlayStation]] as well. EA Sports brand name is used to sponsor English [[Football League Two]] team [[Swindon Town F.C.]] from the 2009\u201310 season onward and the [[EA Sports Cup]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Daryl Holt, Gamelab 2018 (42322570894).jpg|thumb|left|250px|COO and VP Daryl Holt in 2018]]\n\n=== Exclusivity deals ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nIn 2002, EA purchased the license to [[NASCAR]] for six years, ending competition from [[Papyrus Design Group|Papyrus]] and [[Infogrames]]. They lost the NASCAR license in 2009 and the NASCAR license would be owned by [[Polyphony Digital]] for the [[Gran Turismo (series)|''Gran Turismo'' series]] starting with ''[[Gran Turismo 5]]'', and also [[Eutechnyx]] for [[NASCAR The Game (series)|''NASCAR The Game'' series]] until its inception in 2015.\n\nOn December 13, 2004, EA Sports signed an exclusive deal with the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and its Players' Union for five years. On February 12, 2008, EA Sports announced the extension of its exclusive deal until the [[2012 NFL season]].\n\nLess than a month after the NFL Exclusive deal, EA Sports signed a four-year exclusive deal with the [[Arena Football League (1987\u20132008)|Arena Football League]] (AFL).\n\nOn April 11, 2005, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and EA Sports signed a deal to grant EA Sports the sole rights to produce college football games for six years.\n\nEA lost the rights for [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) games to [[2K Sports]] in 2005, ending EA's MVP series; however, EA made [[NCAA Baseball]] games in 2006 and 2007 after losing the MLB license.\n\nIn January 2008, EA Sports decided not to renew their NCAA College Baseball license while they evaluate the status of their MVP game engine.\n\nIn 2005, EA Sports and [[ESPN]] signed a massive 15-year deal for ESPN to be integrated into EA Sports video games from [[2K Sports]] and [[Sega]]. EA's use of the ESPN license has steadily increased over the early life of the deal. EA's early usage of the ESPN license began with ESPN Radio and a sports ticker in titles like Madden NFL, NBA Live, Tiger Woods PGA Tour, and NCAA Baseball and Football. The ESPN integration now includes streaming podcasts, text articles (including content only available previously to ESPN Insider subscribers), and ESPN Motion video (including such programs as ''[[Pardon the Interruption]]'').\n\nIn 2012, EA signs a \"multi-year, multi-product\" partnership with the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], taking over from [[THQ]].\n\nFollowing the release of ''[[Rory McIlroy PGA Tour]]'' in 2015, EA Sports announced that they will end its [[PGA Tour (video game series)|PGA Tour]] series after 25 years, with the said game was pulled from digital storefronts in May 2018. [[2K Sports]] announced that they will assumed their licensing agreement with the [[PGA Tour]] beginning with the release of ''[[The Golf Glub 2019 featuring the PGA Tour]]'' in 2018.\n\n=== PC games ===\nIn June 2009, EA Sports announced that for 2010, the games ''[[Madden NFL]]'', ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]'', ''[[EA Sports NASCAR series|NASCAR]]'', ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]'', ''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'', and ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour]]'' would not be shipped for PC platforms.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=192214 |title=PC News: Peter Moore comes clean on EA SPORTS PC |magazine=[[ComputerAndVideoGames.com]] |access-date=May 29, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704130006/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=192214 |archive-date=July 4, 2008 |date=3 July 2008 |first=Andy |last=Robinson |publisher=[[Future Publishing Limited]]}}</ref> The NCAA Football series had not been released on the PC since 1998, The Tiger Woods series' last PC game was [[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 08]], the NASCAR series had not had a PC version since ''[[NASCAR SimRacing]]'' in 2005, and the last Madden series' to be released on PC was ''[[Madden NFL 08]]''. The NHL series' last PC game was ''[[NHL 09]]''. Likewise, ''[[NBA Live 08]]'' was the final PC version for [[NBA Live]].\n\nThe head of EA Sports at that time, [[Peter Moore (business)|Peter Moore]], cited [[Copyright infringement|piracy]] and the fact that the \"PC as a platform for authentic, licensed, simulation sports games has declined radically in the past three years as the next generation consoles [...] have attracted millions of consumers.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://v1.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/84820-Peter-Moore-Talks-EA-Sports-On-PCs |title=Peter Moore Talks EA Sports On PCs |last=Chalk |first=Andy |date=3 July 2008 |magazine=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |publisher=[[Enthusiast Gaming LLC]] |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref>]\n\nHowever, FIFA series continues to be released on PC, and for the first time since 2008, ''[[Madden NFL 19]]'' was released for Windows and Mac.\n\n=== PlayStation Home ===\n{{Summarize section|date=May 2016}}\nOn April 23, 2009, EA Sports released the long-awaited \"EA Sports Complex\" [[List of PlayStation Home Game Spaces#Game Developer Spaces|space]] for the [[PlayStation 3]]'s online community-based service, [[PlayStation Home]] in the European and North American versions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/04/23/ea-sports-complex-now-live-in-playstation-home/ |title=EA SPORTS Complex Now Live in PlayStation Home |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=9 February 2019 |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212120103/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/04/ea-sports-complex-now-live-in-playstation-home/ |archive-date=December 12, 2009 |author=Locust Star |url-status=live }}</ref> In the Complex, users can play a series of mini-games, including [[poker]], [[kart racing]], [[Miniature golf|golf]], and it also features a Virtual EA Shop. There are also a number of advertisements for upcoming EA Sports games. Each mini-game that the Complex features has a reward or rewards. Heavy Water, a company dedicated to developing for Home, developed the EA Sports Complex for EA Sports.\n\nOriginally, the Complex just featured two rooms: the EA Sports Complex and the EA Sports Complex Upstairs. The EA Sports Complex featured racing and had a golfing range that was unavailable to play. The Upstairs had four poker tables that users could play at any time. With the June 18, 2009 update, the Complex's name changed to the EA Sports Racing Complex and the Upstairs changed to the EA Sports Complex Green Poker Room.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/06/17/coming-to-playstation-home-new-socom-space-ghostbusters-apartment-ea-sports-complex-update-more/ |title=Coming to PlayStation Home: New SOCOM Space, Ghostbusters Apartment, EA SPORTS Complex Update + More! |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locust Star |date=17 June 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821062510/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/06/17/coming-to-playstation-home-new-socom-space-ghostbusters-apartment-ea-sports-complex-update-more/ |archive-date=August 21, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other than the name change, the update took away the golfing range and added four more karts for users to play Racing at and it also added one red poker table to the poker room.\n\nThe July 2, 2009 update added golf and another poker room making four rooms for the Complex; the EA Sports Racing Complex, the EA Sports Golf Complex, the EA Sports Complex Green Poker Room, and the EA Sports Complex Red Poker Room. The Racing Complex features Racing with a total of eight karts; four on each side of the Complex. The Golf Complex features two Practice Ranges for golfing; one range on each side of the Complex. A Golf Pro-shop is coming soon for the Golf Complex. The Green Poker Room featured four green poker tables that users can play anytime. The Red Poker Room featured four red poker tables but requires users to have 2,000 points to play.\n\nOn July 16, 2009, EA Sports released another room for the Complex making five rooms for the Complex. This room is the [[List of PlayStation Home Game Spaces|game space]] for ''Fight Night Round 4'' called \"Club Fight Night\" featuring a mini-game called Club DJ and coming soon, robot boxing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/07/15/this-week-in-playstation-home-buzz-and-fight-night-space-launches-and-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: BUZZ! and Fight Night Space Launches, and More! |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locst Star |date=15 July 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090920153530/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/07/this-week-in-playstation-home-buzz-and-fight-night-space-launches-and-more/ |archive-date=September 20, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2009, EA Sports added a Black Poker Table to the EA Sports Complex Red Poker Room for the higher level players. In time, there will be a room dedicated for this table just like the Green Poker Room and the Red Poker Room. They also added a fifth green table to the Green Poker Room. The update also included the addition of the EA Sports Pro Shop where users can purchase full boxing outfits and furniture from ''Fight Night Round 4''. The Pro Shop is found in the Racing Complex. The August 16, 2009 update replaced the fifth green table in the Green Poker Room with a red table. They also reduced the number of points for the Black Table from 20,000 to 10,000. The August 27, 2009 update separated the scoreboards for each level of play \u2013 Green, Red, and Black \u2013 and into Daily boards and Season boards (left side and right side), improved card readability, additional rail seating near the poker tables, player removal on lockup while playing poker, and player buy-in refund on removal (does not refund on Home disconnect) while playing poker.\n\nOn October 9, 2009, EA Sports released the EA Sports Complex to the Japanese version of Home. They also released [[NFL]] jerseys for every team in the league for purchase inside of the EA Sports Complex and in Home's shopping complex. EA Sports have also teamed up with the Home team to produce and distribute exclusive virtual items that serve to support [[National Breast Cancer Awareness Month]]. 100% of proceeds for these items went go to the Brees Dream Foundation in support of breast cancer research and awareness programs. The items are black jerseys with a pink number 9 on the front and the name Brees on the back also in pink. These jerseys were available from October 15, 2009 to November 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/10/nfl-comes-to-playstation-home-dethklok-pixeljunk-museum-and-motorstorm-personal-space/ |title=NFL Comes to PlayStation Home + Dethklok, PixelJunk Museum and MotorStorm Personal Space |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locust Star |date=7 October 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212075931/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/10/nfl-comes-to-playstation-home-dethklok-pixeljunk-museum-and-motorstorm-personal-space/ |archive-date=December 12, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 5, 2009, for those who purchased the Brees Breast Cancer jersey, they received a free DJ kit that is featured in the Club Fight Night space by entering one of the two EA Sports Complex poker rooms between November 5, 2009 and November 25, 2009. On November 25, 2009, ''Fight Night Round 4'' producers Mike Mahar and Brian Hayes were in Home between the hours of 4:00pm and 5:00pm PT (7:00pm and 8:00pm EST), for a live chat with the PlayStation Home community in one instance of the Club Fight Night space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/11/this-week-in-playstation-home-new-red-bull-space-event-fight-night-producer-chat-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: New Red Bull Space + Event, Fight Night Producer Chat & More |date=November 25, 2009 |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=November 25, 2009 |author=Locust Star |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128060854/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/11/this-week-in-playstation-home-new-red-bull-space-event-fight-night-producer-chat-more |archive-date=November 28, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 7, 2010, EA Sports released [[NCAA]] college football jerseys in the EA Sports Complex and in Home's shopping complex.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2010/01/this-week-in-playstation-home-waterfall-terrace-personal-space-ncaa-football-jerseys-loads-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: Waterfall Terrace Personal Space, NCAA Football Jerseys, + Loads More! |date=January 6, 2010 |author=Locust Star |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=January 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109140659/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2010/01/this-week-in-playstation-home-waterfall-terrace-personal-space-ncaa-football-jerseys-loads-more/ |archive-date=January 9, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2011, EA Sports launched the EA Sports Season Ticket subscription service. It was discontinued in 2015 and it was replaced with the similar [[EA Access]] service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.origin.com/gbr/en-us/store/origin-access |title=Origin Access |publisher=[[EA Access]] |access-date=August 12, 2018 |work=Origin.com}}</ref>\n\n== Franchises ==\n{{Main|List of Electronic Arts games}}\nMost EA Sports games are distinguished by year, as most games are released on a yearly basis. Nevertheless, as EA Sports is the leading purchaser of official licenses, it is not uncommon that in a short span several games of the same sport but with different licenses are released: ''FIFA: Road to World Cup 98'' was shortly followed by ''FIFA 98'' and then ''World Cup 98'', all in the wake of ''FIFA Soccer Manager'' in 1997 (as EA has the license for the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Football Championship|European Football Championship]], each happening regularly in four-year intervals), and college football and basketball games are released that are based on Madden NFL and NBA Live, respectively.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Series\n! Sport\n! First release\n! Latest release\n! Upcoming release\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL|Madden]]''\n| [[American football]]\n| ''[[John Madden Football (1988 video game)|John Madden Football]]'' (1988)\n| ''[[Madden NFL 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[NBA Live]]''\n| [[Basketball]]\n| ''[[NBA Live 95]]'' (1994)\n| ''[[NBA Live 19]]'' (2018)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]''\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| ''[[NHL Hockey]]'' (1991)\n| ''[[NHL 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]''\n| [[Association football]]\n| ''[[FIFA International Soccer]]'' (1993)\n|''[[FIFA 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC|UFC]]''\n| [[Mixed martial arts]]\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC]]'' (2014)\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC 3]]'' (2018)\n|\n|}\n\n=== Former ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Series\n! Sport\n! First release\n! Last release\n|-\n| ''[[PGA Tour (video game series)|PGA Tour]]''\n| [[Golf]]\n| ''[[PGA Tour Golf]]'' (1990)\n| ''[[Rory McIlroy PGA Tour]]'' (2015)\n|-\n| ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]''\n| [[NCAA Football]]\n| ''[[Bill Walsh College Football]]'' (1993)\n| ''[[NCAA Football 14]]'' (2013)\n|-\n| ''Mutant League Football''\n| [[American Football]]\n| ''[[Mutant League Football]]'' (1993)\n|\n|-\n| ''Mutant League Hockey''\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| ''[[Mutant League Hockey]]'' (1994)\n|\n|-\n| ''Mario Andretti Racing\n| [[Auto racing]]\n| ''[[Mario Andretti Racing]]'' (1994)\n| ''[[Andretti Racing]]'' (1996)\n|-\n| ''Australian Rugby League''\n| [[Rugby league]]\n| ''[[Australian Rugby League (video game)|Australian Rugby League]]'' (1995)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Cricket (series)|Cricket]]''\n| [[Cricket]]\n| ''[[Cricket (series)#Cricket 96|Cricket 96]]'' (1996)\n| ''[[Cricket (series)#Cricket 07|Cricket 07]]'' (2006)\n|-\n| ''[[Triple Play series|Triple Play]]'' / ''[[MVP Baseball series|MVP Baseball]]''\n| [[MLB Baseball]]\n| ''Triple Play 97'' (1996)\n| ''[[MVP Baseball 2005]]'' (2005)\n|-\n| ''[[EA Sports NASCAR series|NASCAR]]''\n| [[Stock car racing]]\n| ''[[NASCAR 98]]'' (1997)\n| ''[[NASCAR 09]]'' / ''[[NASCAR Kart Racing]]'' (2009)\n|-\n| ''[[AFL (video game series)|AFL]]''\n| [[Australian football]]\n| ''[[AFL (video game series)#AFL 98|AFL 98]]'' (1997)\n| ''[[AFL (video game series)#AFL 99|AFL 99]]'' (1998)\n|-\n| ''[[FIFA Manager]]''\n| [[Association football]] management\n| ''[[FIFA Manager#FIFA Soccer Manager|FIFA Soccer Manager]]'' (1997)\n| ''[[FIFA Manager#FIFA Manager 14|FIFA Manager 14]]'' (2013)\n|-\n| ''[[NCAA Basketball series|NCAA Basketball]]''\n| [[NCAA Basketball]]\n| ''[[NCAA Basketball series#NCAA March Madness 98|NCAA March Madness 98]]'' (1998)\n| ''[[NCAA Basketball 10]]'' (2009)\n|-\n|''[[Knockout Kings]]'' / ''[[Fight Night (EA video game series)|Fight Night]]''\n| [[Boxing]]\n| ''[[Knockout Kings (video game)|Knockout Kings]]'' (1998)\n| ''[[Fight Night Champion]]'' (2011)\n|-\n| ''Superbike''\n| [[Superbike]]\n| ''Superbike World Championship'' (1999)\n| ''[[Superbike 2001]]'' (2000)\n|-\n| ''Supercars''\n| [[Supercars Championship|Supercars]]\n| ''[[Digital Illusions CE|V8 Challenge]]'' (2002)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[SSX (series)|SSX]]''\n| [[Snowboarding]]\n| ''[[SSX]]'' (2000)\n| ''[[SSX (2012 video game)|SSX]]'' (2012)\n|-\n| ''[[EA Sports F1 series|F1]]''\n| [[Formula One]]\n| ''[[F1 2000 (video game)|F1 2000]]'' (2000)\n| ''[[EA Sports F1 series#F1 Challenge '99-'02|F1 Challenge '99\u2013'02]]'' (2003)\n|-\n| ''Rugby''\n| [[Rugby union]]\n| ''[[Rugby (video game)|Rugby]]'' (2000)\n| ''[[Rugby 08]]'' (2007)\n|-\n| ''[[NBA Street]]''\n| [[Streetball]]\n| ''[[NBA Street]]'' (2001)\n| ''[[NBA Street Homecourt]]'' (2007)\n|-\n| ''[[NFL Street (series)|NFL Street]]''\n| [[Street football (American)|Street football]]\n| ''[[NFL Street]]'' (2004)\n| ''[[NFL Street 3]]'' (2006)\n|-\n| ''[[FIFA Street]]''\n| [[Association football]]\n| ''[[FIFA Street]]'' (2005)\n| ''[[FIFA Street (2012 video game)|FIFA Street]]'' (2012)\n|-\n| ''MVP: NCAA Baseball''\n| [[NCAA Baseball]]\n| ''[[MVP 06: NCAA Baseball]]'' (2006)\n| ''[[MVP 07: NCAA Baseball]]'' (2007)\n|-\n| ''Arena Football\n| [[Arena football]]\n| ''[[Arena Football (2006 video game)|Arena Football]]'' (2006)\n| ''[[Arena Football: Road to Glory]]'' (2007)\n|-\n| ''EA Sports Active''\n| [[Physical exercise|Training]]\n| ''[[EA Sports Active]]'' (2009)\n| ''[[EA Sports Active 2]] (2010)\n|-\n| ''Grand Slam Tennis''\n| [[Tennis]]\n| ''[[Grand Slam Tennis]]'' (2009)\n| ''[[Grand Slam Tennis 2]]'' (2012)\n|-\n| ''MMA''\n| [[Mixed martial arts]]\n| ''[[EA Sports MMA]]'' (2010)\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.easports.com/}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Electronic Arts}}\n{{EA-NBA-Live-series}}\n{{NBA Jam}}\n{{NCAA Basketball series}}\n{{Fight Night series}}\n{{MaddenNFL-Games}}\n{{NCAA Football games}}\n{{EA Sports NASCAR series}}\n{{Tiger Woods PGA Tour}}\n{{NHL series}}\n{{Football video games by Electronic Arts}}\n{{Rugby Union video games by Electronic Arts}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1991 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American brands]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts]]\n[[Category:Entertainment Software Association]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1991]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = EA Sports\n| logo = EA Sports.svg\n| former_names = Electronic Arts Sports Network (1991\u20131993)\n| type = [[Division (business)|Division]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1991}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people = Daryl Holt ([[Chief operating officer|COO]] and [[Vice-president|VP]])\n| num_employees =\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[Electronic Arts]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.easports.com/|easports.com}}\n}}\n\n'''EA Sports''' is a division of [[Electronic Arts]] that develops and publishes [[Sports game|sports video games]].  Formerly a marketing gimmick of Electronic Arts, in which they tried to imitate real-life sports networks by calling themselves the \"EA Sports Network\" (EASN) with pictures or endorsements with real commentators such as [[John Madden]], it soon grew up to become a sub-label on its own, releasing game series such as ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]'', ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]'', ''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'' and ''[[Madden NFL]]''.\n\nMost games under this brand are developed by [[EA Vancouver]], the studio of Electronic Arts in [[Burnaby]], [[British Columbia]] as well as [[EA Tiburon]] in [[Maitland, Florida]]. The main rival to EA Sports is [[2K Sports]]. Notably, both companies compete over the realm of NBA games. [[Konami]] is its rival in association football games.\n\nUnlike some other sports game companies, EA Sports has no special ties to a single platform, which means that all games are released for the bestselling active platforms, sometimes long after most of the other companies abandon them. For example, ''[[FIFA: Road to World Cup 98|FIFA 98]]'', ''[[Madden NFL 98]]'', ''[[NBA Live 98]]'', and ''[[NHL 98]]'' were released for the [[Sega Genesis]] and the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] throughout 1997; ''[[Madden NFL 2005]]'' and ''[[FIFA Football 2005|FIFA 2005]]'' had [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] releases in 2004 (''FIFA 2005'' and ''Madden NFL 2005'' were also the last two PlayStation titles to be released); and ''[[NCAA Football 08]]'' had an [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] release in 2007. ''[[Madden NFL 08]]'' also had [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] and Nintendo [[GameCube]] releases in 2007, and was the final title released for the GameCube, with ''[[Madden NFL 09]]'' following as the final Xbox title. Additionally, ''[[NASCAR Thunder 2003]]'' and ''[[NASCAR Thunder 2004]]'' were released not only for the [[PlayStation 2]], but for the original [[PlayStation]] as well. EA Sports brand name is used to sponsor English [[Football League Two]] team [[Swindon Town F.C.]] from the 2009\u201310 season onward and the [[EA Sports Cup]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Daryl Holt, Gamelab 2018 (42322570894).jpg|thumb|left|250px|COO and VP Daryl Holt in 2018]]\n\n=== Exclusivity deals ===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nIn 2002, EA purchased the license to [[NASCAR]] for six years, ending competition from [[Papyrus Design Group|Papyrus]] and [[Infogrames]]. They lost the NASCAR license in 2009 and the NASCAR license would be owned by [[Polyphony Digital]] for the [[Gran Turismo (series)|''Gran Turismo'' series]] starting with ''[[Gran Turismo 5]]'', and also [[Eutechnyx]] for [[NASCAR The Game (series)|''NASCAR The Game'' series]] until its inception in 2015.\n\nOn December 13, 2004, EA Sports signed an exclusive deal with the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and its Players' Union for five years. On February 12, 2008, EA Sports announced the extension of its exclusive deal until the [[2012 NFL season]].\n\nLess than a month after the NFL Exclusive deal, EA Sports signed a four-year exclusive deal with the [[Arena Football League (1987\u20132008)|Arena Football League]] (AFL).\n\nOn April 11, 2005, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and EA Sports signed a deal to grant EA Sports the sole rights to produce college football games for six years.\n\nEA lost the rights for [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) games to [[2K Sports]] in 2005, ending EA's MVP series; however, EA made [[NCAA Baseball]] games in 2006 and 2007 after losing the MLB license.\n\nIn January 2008, EA Sports decided not to renew their NCAA College Baseball license while they evaluate the status of their MVP game engine.\n\nIn 2005, EA Sports and [[ESPN]] signed a massive 15-year deal for ESPN to be integrated into EA Sports video games from [[2K Sports]] and [[Sega]]. EA's use of the ESPN license has steadily increased over the early life of the deal. EA's early usage of the ESPN license began with ESPN Radio and a sports ticker in titles like Madden NFL, NBA Live, Tiger Woods PGA Tour, and NCAA Baseball and Football. The ESPN integration now includes streaming podcasts, text articles (including content only available previously to ESPN Insider subscribers), and ESPN Motion video (including such programs as ''[[Pardon the Interruption]]'').\n\nIn 2012, EA signs a \"multi-year, multi-product\" partnership with the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], taking over from [[THQ]].\n\nFollowing the release of ''[[Rory McIlroy PGA Tour]]'' in 2015, EA Sports announced that they will end its [[PGA Tour (video game series)|PGA Tour]] series after 25 years, with the said game was pulled from digital storefronts in May 2018. [[2K Sports]] announced that they will assumed their licensing agreement with the [[PGA Tour]] beginning with the release of ''[[The Golf Glub 2019 featuring the PGA Tour]]'' in 2018.\n\n=== PC games ===\nIn June 2009, EA Sports announced that for 2010, the games ''[[Madden NFL]]'', ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]'', ''[[EA Sports NASCAR series|NASCAR]]'', ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]'', ''[[NBA Live (video game series)|NBA Live]]'', and ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour]]'' would not be shipped for PC platforms.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=192214 |title=PC News: Peter Moore comes clean on EA SPORTS PC |magazine=[[ComputerAndVideoGames.com]] |access-date=May 29, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704130006/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=192214 |archive-date=July 4, 2008 |date=3 July 2008 |first=Andy |last=Robinson |publisher=[[Future Publishing Limited]]}}</ref> The NCAA Football series had not been released on the PC since 1998, The Tiger Woods series' last PC game was [[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 08]], the NASCAR series had not had a PC version since ''[[NASCAR SimRacing]]'' in 2005, and the last Madden series' to be released on PC was ''[[Madden NFL 08]]''. The NHL series' last PC game was ''[[NHL 09]]''. Likewise, ''[[NBA Live 08]]'' was the final PC version for [[NBA Live]].\n\nThe head of EA Sports at that time, [[Peter Moore (business)|Peter Moore]], cited [[Copyright infringement|piracy]] and the fact that the \"PC as a platform for authentic, licensed, simulation sports games has declined radically in the past three years as the next generation consoles [...] have attracted millions of consumers.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://v1.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/84820-Peter-Moore-Talks-EA-Sports-On-PCs |title=Peter Moore Talks EA Sports On PCs |last=Chalk |first=Andy |date=3 July 2008 |magazine=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]] |publisher=[[Enthusiast Gaming LLC]] |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref>]\n\nHowever, FIFA series continues to be released on PC, and for the first time since 2008, ''[[Madden NFL 19]]'' was released for Windows and Mac.\n\n=== PlayStation Home ===\n{{Summarize section|date=May 2016}}\nOn April 23, 2009, EA Sports released the long-awaited \"EA Sports Complex\" [[List of PlayStation Home Game Spaces#Game Developer Spaces|space]] for the [[PlayStation 3]]'s online community-based service, [[PlayStation Home]] in the European and North American versions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/04/23/ea-sports-complex-now-live-in-playstation-home/ |title=EA SPORTS Complex Now Live in PlayStation Home |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=9 February 2019 |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212120103/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/04/ea-sports-complex-now-live-in-playstation-home/ |archive-date=December 12, 2009 |author=Locust Star |url-status=live }}</ref> In the Complex, users can play a series of mini-games, including [[poker]], [[kart racing]], [[Miniature golf|golf]], and it also features a Virtual EA Shop. There are also a number of advertisements for upcoming EA Sports games. Each mini-game that the Complex features has a reward or rewards. Heavy Water, a company dedicated to developing for Home, developed the EA Sports Complex for EA Sports.\n\nOriginally, the Complex just featured two rooms: the EA Sports Complex and the EA Sports Complex Upstairs. The EA Sports Complex featured racing and had a golfing range that was unavailable to play. The Upstairs had four poker tables that users could play at any time. With the June 18, 2009 update, the Complex's name changed to the EA Sports Racing Complex and the Upstairs changed to the EA Sports Complex Green Poker Room.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/06/17/coming-to-playstation-home-new-socom-space-ghostbusters-apartment-ea-sports-complex-update-more/ |title=Coming to PlayStation Home: New SOCOM Space, Ghostbusters Apartment, EA SPORTS Complex Update + More! |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locust Star |date=17 June 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821062510/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/06/17/coming-to-playstation-home-new-socom-space-ghostbusters-apartment-ea-sports-complex-update-more/ |archive-date=August 21, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Other than the name change, the update took away the golfing range and added four more karts for users to play Racing at and it also added one red poker table to the poker room.\n\nThe July 2, 2009 update added golf and another poker room making four rooms for the Complex; the EA Sports Racing Complex, the EA Sports Golf Complex, the EA Sports Complex Green Poker Room, and the EA Sports Complex Red Poker Room. The Racing Complex features Racing with a total of eight karts; four on each side of the Complex. The Golf Complex features two Practice Ranges for golfing; one range on each side of the Complex. A Golf Pro-shop is coming soon for the Golf Complex. The Green Poker Room featured four green poker tables that users can play anytime. The Red Poker Room featured four red poker tables but requires users to have 2,000 points to play.\n\nOn July 16, 2009, EA Sports released another room for the Complex making five rooms for the Complex. This room is the [[List of PlayStation Home Game Spaces|game space]] for ''Fight Night Round 4'' called \"Club Fight Night\" featuring a mini-game called Club DJ and coming soon, robot boxing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/07/15/this-week-in-playstation-home-buzz-and-fight-night-space-launches-and-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: BUZZ! and Fight Night Space Launches, and More! |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locst Star |date=15 July 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090920153530/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/07/this-week-in-playstation-home-buzz-and-fight-night-space-launches-and-more/ |archive-date=September 20, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2009, EA Sports added a Black Poker Table to the EA Sports Complex Red Poker Room for the higher level players. In time, there will be a room dedicated for this table just like the Green Poker Room and the Red Poker Room. They also added a fifth green table to the Green Poker Room. The update also included the addition of the EA Sports Pro Shop where users can purchase full boxing outfits and furniture from ''Fight Night Round 4''. The Pro Shop is found in the Racing Complex. The August 16, 2009 update replaced the fifth green table in the Green Poker Room with a red table. They also reduced the number of points for the Black Table from 20,000 to 10,000. The August 27, 2009 update separated the scoreboards for each level of play \u2013 Green, Red, and Black \u2013 and into Daily boards and Season boards (left side and right side), improved card readability, additional rail seating near the poker tables, player removal on lockup while playing poker, and player buy-in refund on removal (does not refund on Home disconnect) while playing poker.\n\nOn October 9, 2009, EA Sports released the EA Sports Complex to the Japanese version of Home. They also released [[NFL]] jerseys for every team in the league for purchase inside of the EA Sports Complex and in Home's shopping complex. EA Sports have also teamed up with the Home team to produce and distribute exclusive virtual items that serve to support [[National Breast Cancer Awareness Month]]. 100% of proceeds for these items went go to the Brees Dream Foundation in support of breast cancer research and awareness programs. The items are black jerseys with a pink number 9 on the front and the name Brees on the back also in pink. These jerseys were available from October 15, 2009 to November 25, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/10/nfl-comes-to-playstation-home-dethklok-pixeljunk-museum-and-motorstorm-personal-space/ |title=NFL Comes to PlayStation Home + Dethklok, PixelJunk Museum and MotorStorm Personal Space |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |author=Locust Star |date=7 October 2009 |access-date=9 February 2019 |work=[[PlayStation Blog]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212075931/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/10/nfl-comes-to-playstation-home-dethklok-pixeljunk-museum-and-motorstorm-personal-space/ |archive-date=December 12, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 5, 2009, for those who purchased the Brees Breast Cancer jersey, they received a free DJ kit that is featured in the Club Fight Night space by entering one of the two EA Sports Complex poker rooms between November 5, 2009 and November 25, 2009. On November 25, 2009, ''Fight Night Round 4'' producers Mike Mahar and Brian Hayes were in Home between the hours of 4:00pm and 5:00pm PT (7:00pm and 8:00pm EST), for a live chat with the PlayStation Home community in one instance of the Club Fight Night space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/11/this-week-in-playstation-home-new-red-bull-space-event-fight-night-producer-chat-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: New Red Bull Space + Event, Fight Night Producer Chat & More |date=November 25, 2009 |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=November 25, 2009 |author=Locust Star |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128060854/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2009/11/this-week-in-playstation-home-new-red-bull-space-event-fight-night-producer-chat-more |archive-date=November 28, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 7, 2010, EA Sports released [[NCAA]] college football jerseys in the EA Sports Complex and in Home's shopping complex.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2010/01/this-week-in-playstation-home-waterfall-terrace-personal-space-ncaa-football-jerseys-loads-more/ |title=This Week in PlayStation Home: Waterfall Terrace Personal Space, NCAA Football Jerseys, + Loads More! |date=January 6, 2010 |author=Locust Star |publisher=[[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |access-date=January 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109140659/http://blog.us.playstation.com/2010/01/this-week-in-playstation-home-waterfall-terrace-personal-space-ncaa-football-jerseys-loads-more/ |archive-date=January 9, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2011, EA Sports launched the EA Sports Season Ticket subscription service. It was discontinued in 2015 and it was replaced with the similar [[EA Access]] service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.origin.com/gbr/en-us/store/origin-access |title=Origin Access |publisher=[[EA Access]] |access-date=August 12, 2018 |work=Origin.com}}</ref>\n\n== Franchises ==\n{{Main|List of Electronic Arts games}}\nMost EA Sports games are distinguished by year, as most games are released on a yearly basis. Nevertheless, as EA Sports is the leading purchaser of official licenses, it is not uncommon that in a short span several games of the same sport but with different licenses are released: ''FIFA: Road to World Cup 98'' was shortly followed by ''FIFA 98'' and then ''World Cup 98'', all in the wake of ''FIFA Soccer Manager'' in 1997 (as EA has the license for the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Football Championship|European Football Championship]], each happening regularly in four-year intervals), and college football and basketball games are released that are based on Madden NFL and NBA Live, respectively.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Series\n! Sport\n! First release\n! Latest release\n! Upcoming release\n|-\n| ''[[Madden NFL|Madden]]''\n| [[American football]]\n| ''[[John Madden Football (1988 video game)|John Madden Football]]'' (1988)\n| ''[[Madden NFL 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[NBA Live]]''\n| [[Basketball]]\n| ''[[NBA Live 95]]'' (1994)\n| ''[[NBA Live 19]]'' (2018)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[NHL (video game series)|NHL]]''\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| ''[[NHL Hockey]]'' (1991)\n| ''[[NHL 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]''\n| [[Association football]]\n| ''[[FIFA International Soccer]]'' (1993)\n|''[[FIFA 20]]'' (2019)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC|UFC]]''\n| [[Mixed martial arts]]\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC]]'' (2014)\n| ''[[EA Sports UFC 3]]'' (2018)\n|\n|}\n\n=== Former ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Series\n! Sport\n! First release\n! Last release\n|-\n| ''[[PGA Tour (video game series)|PGA Tour]]''\n| [[Golf]]\n| ''[[PGA Tour Golf]]'' (1990)\n| ''[[Rory McIlroy PGA Tour]]'' (2015)\n|-\n| ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]''\n| [[NCAA Football]]\n| ''[[Bill Walsh College Football]]'' (1993)\n| ''[[NCAA Football 14]]'' (2013)\n|-\n| ''Mutant League Football''\n| [[American Football]]\n| ''[[Mutant League Football]]'' (1993)\n|\n|-\n| ''Mutant League Hockey''\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| ''[[Mutant League Hockey]]'' (1994)\n|\n|-\n| ''Mario Andretti Racing\n| [[Auto racing]]\n| ''[[Mario Andretti Racing]]'' (1994)\n| ''[[Andretti Racing]]'' (1996)\n|-\n| ''Australian Rugby League''\n| [[Rugby league]]\n| ''[[Australian Rugby League (video game)|Australian Rugby League]]'' (1995)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Cricket (series)|Cricket]]''\n| [[Cricket]]\n| ''[[Cricket (series)#Cricket 96|Cricket 96]]'' (1996)\n| ''[[Cricket (series)#Cricket 07|Cricket 07]]'' (2006)\n|-\n| ''[[Triple Play series|Triple Play]]'' / ''[[MVP Baseball series|MVP Baseball]]''\n|